column2:
How does COVID-19 spread?
People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales These droplets land on objects
column3: and have been implicated in gastroenteritis in infants. A novel coronavirus was identified as the cause of a worldwide outbreak of a Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) in 2003. This outbreak caused by the virus is believed to have originated in Guangdong south China.
column4:
It predominantly affected mainly China, Hong Kong, Singapore, and Taiwan. Subsequently, this outbreak spread to neighboring countries in Asia, Canada, and the United States.
In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging
column5: from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS). The most recently discovered coronavirus causes coronavirus disease COVID-19.
column6:
What is COVID-19?
COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus. This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in December 2019
column7:
What are the symptoms of COVID-19?
The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually.
column8: Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms and don't feel unwell. Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing.
column9: surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth.
column10: People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.
column11: World Health Organisation is assessing ongoing research on the ways COVID-19 is spread. https://t.co/ItmFmb8ghD

column4: 3. The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually.
column5: 4. Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms and don't feel unwell. Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing.
column6: 8. People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.
column7:
9. Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?

Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.  See previous answer on ‚ÄúHow does COVID-19 spread?
column8:
10. Can CoVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?

The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low.
column9: 11. However, many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms. This is particularly true at the early stages of the disease. It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill.
column10: 13. Many countries around the world have seen cases of COVID-19 and several have seen outbreaks. Authorities in China and some other countries have succeeded in slowing or stopping their outbreaks.
column11:
13.(A)
However, the situation is unpredictable so check regularly for the latest news.

You can reduce your chances of being infected or spreading COVID-19 by taking some simple precautions:
column12:
13.(B)
Regularly and thoroughly clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.
Why? Washing your hands with soap and water or using alcohol-based hand rub kills viruses that may be on your hands.
column13:
13. (C)
Maintain at least 1 metre (3 feet) distance between yourself and anyone who is coughing or sneezing.
Why? When someone coughs or sneezes they spray small liquid droplets from their nose or mouth which may contain virus.
column14: 13. (C)...  If you are too close, you can breathe in the droplets, including the COVID-19 virus if the person coughing has the disease.

column2:
The Coronavirus Outbreak
Answers to your most common questions:
Updated March 2, 2020

What is a coronavirus?
It is a novel virus named for the crownlike spikes that protrude from its surface. The coronavirus can infect both animals and people and can
column3:
and people and can cause a range of respiratory illnesses from the common cold to lung lesions and pneumonia.
How contagious is the virus?
It seems to spread very easily from person to person, especially in homes, hospitals and other confined spaces.
column4:
The pathogen can travel through the air, enveloped in tiny respiratory droplets that are produced when a sick person breathes, talks, coughs or sneezes.Where has the virus spread?
The virus, which originated in Wuhan, China, has sickened more than 89,700 in
column5:
at least 67 countries and more than 3,000 have died. The spread has slowed in China, but is picking up speed in Europe and the United States.
What symptoms should I look out for?
Symptoms, which can take between two to 14 days to appear, include fever, cough
column6:
and difficulty breathing or shortness of breath. Milder cases may resemble the flu or a bad cold, but people may be able to pass on the virus even before they develop symptoms.
How do I keep myself and others safe?
Washing your hands frequently is the most
column7:
the most important thing you can do, along with staying at home when you‚Äôre sick and avoiding touching your face.
How can I prepare for a possible outbreak?
Keep a 30-day supply of essential medicines. Get a flu shot. Have essential household items on hand.
column8:
Have a support system in place for elderly family members.
What if I‚Äôm traveling?
The C.D.C. has advised against all non-essential travel to South Korea, China, Italy and Iran. And the agency has warned older and at-risk travelers to avoid Japan.
column9:
How long will it take to develop a treatment or vaccine?
Several drugs are being tested, and some initial findings are expected soon. A vaccine to stop the spread is still at least a year away.

column2:
MISCONCEPTIONS

¬†1.) COVID-19 is just like the flu/another strain of the flu.

¬†2.) COVID-19 is not as infectious nor as deadly as the seasonal flu.

¬†3.) Younger individuals should not be worried about the virus.
column3: Of greater concern to younger individuals, and in fact everyone should be the expected reemergence of COVID-19 in this coming fall. (4) The reemergence of infectious diseases in the fall typically is accompanied by mutations to the infectious agent enabling it to infect
column4:
all individuals, young and old and typically more virulent as well.(5) Which brings me to point #4.¬†
¬†4.) The actions mandated by public health officials, schools, and businesses worldwide are by no accounts an overreaction.
column5: The prevention of the spread of disease not only helps our health professionals, hospitals, and public health organizations treat individuals, but also decreases risk of mutations in COVID-19 which would be responsible for a reemergence of COVID-19 in the fall able to severely
column6: affect all individuals as the more COVID-19 is able to replicate in a host the more likely a beneficial mutation (from perspective of the virus) is to arise. (6) The stopping of the spread of COVID-19 now is CRUCIAL to preventing the spread later, and for protecting the elderly,
column7: immunocompromised, and those with pre-existing conditions. It should also be noted that not extending the course of the COVID-19 virus in the population disproportionately affects those of lower socioeconomic statuses and those who are more likely to return to their workplace as
column8:
a result of financial need leading to increased spread. (7,8)

I would never make a claim to be an expert on this topic, and I applaud and look up to those who have spent their lives conducting research on infectious diseases.
column9: I am, however, passionate about this particular area of science and passionate about education and educating the general public about infectious diseases. I highly encourage everyone of you to do your research, educate yourself on how you can best help yourself, your family,
column10: and your community. The efforts to stop the spread of this disease begin on the individual level and are part of a global effort. The actions of individuals today will have resounding impacts in months and years to come.
column11:
I urge you to be safe and think of others in addition to yourself.¬†

column2:
Cold weather and snow CANNOT kill the new coronavirus.
There is no reason to believe that cold weather can kill the new coronavirus or other diseases. The normal human body temperature remains around 36.5¬∞C to 37¬∞C, regardless of the external temperature or weather.
column3: By doing this you eliminate viruses that may be on your hands and avoid infection that could occur by then touching your eyes, mouth, and nose. https://t.co/H8M0OgibEU
column4: The new coronavirus is a respiratory virus which spreads primarily through droplets generated when an infected person coughs or sneezes, or through droplets of saliva or discharge from the nose.
column5: To protect yourself, clean your hands frequently with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water. Also, avoid close contact with anyone who is coughing and sneezing. https://t.co/kSdfGWv5GI
column6:
Are hand dryers effective in killing the new coronavirus?
No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV. To protect yourself against the new coronavirus, you should frequently clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.
column7: Once your hands are cleaned, you should dry them thoroughly by using paper towels or a warm air dryer. https://t.co/sJhxDjdhrA
column8:
Can an ultraviolet disinfection lamp kill the new coronavirus?
UV lamps should not be used to sterilize hands or other areas of skin as UV radiation can cause skin irritation. https://t.co/2pmp1tHJwG
column9:
How effective are thermal scanners in detecting people infected with the new coronavirus?
Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus.
column10: However, they cannot detect people who are infected but are not yet sick with fever. This is because it takes between 2 and 10 days before people who are infected become sick and develop a fever. https://t.co/KnrTczQAWn
column11:
Can spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body kill the new coronavirus?
No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body.
column12: Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes (i.e. eyes, mouth). Be aware that both alcohol and chlorine can be useful to disinfect surfaces, but they need to be used under appropriate recommendations. https://t.co/wd5VHaUFan
column13:
Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against the new coronavirus?
No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.
column14: The virus is so new and different that it needs its own vaccine. Researchers are trying to develop a vaccine against 2019-nCoV, and WHO is supporting their efforts.
column15: Although these vaccines are not effective against 2019-nCoV, vaccination against respiratory illnesses is highly recommended to protect your health. https://t.co/Qu00YqTLMP
column16:
Can regularly rinsing your nose with saline help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus.
column17: There is some limited evidence that regularly rinsing nose with saline can help people recover more quickly from the common cold. However, regularly rinsing the nose has not been shown to prevent respiratory infections. https://t.co/U63r6XI6p6
column18:
Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus. https://t.co/yaLUTNsWGV
column19:
Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?
People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column20: Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus.
column21: WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene. https://t.co/bThbxOL21K
column22:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?
No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria. The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column23: However, if you are hospitalized for the 2019-nCoV, you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible. https://t.co/WpTNgsfJMU
column24:
Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?
To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column25: However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized supportive care.
column26:
Some specific treatments are under investigation, and will be tested through clinical trials. WHO is helping to accelerate research and development efforts with a range or partners.

Q: Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new #coronavirus (2019-nCoV)?

A: No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.
The 2019-nC0V is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should  not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.

üêæ *Can humans become infected with the COVID-19 from an animal source?*
Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses that are common in animals.
column3: While initial investigations suggest the virus may be present in feces in some cases, spread through this route is not a main feature of the outbreak. WHO is assessing ongoing research on the ways COVID-19 is spread and will continue to share new findings.
column4: Occasionally, people get infected with these viruses which may then spread to other people. For example, SARS-CoV was associated with civet cats and MERS-CoV is transmitted by dromedary camels. Possible animal sources of COVID-19 have not yet been confirmed.
column5: To protect yourself, such as when visiting live animal markets, avoid direct contact with animals and surfaces in contact with animals. Ensure good food safety practices at all times.
column6: Handle raw meat, milk or animal organs with care to avoid contamination of uncooked foods and avoid consuming raw or undercooked animal products.
column7:
üê∂ *Can I catch COVID-19 from my pet?*
There is no evidence that a dog, cat or any pet can transmit COVID-19. COVID-19 is mainly spread through droplets produced when an infected person coughs, sneezes or speaks. To protect yourself clean your hands frequently and thoroughly.

column2: @_sh4 NY/NJ/CT continue to trend down in daily new cases even as many other states have either stopped their downward trend or inflected upward since the mass protests started. Estimates of prevalence are 20-25%, well below the herd immunity threshold. So what is going on?
column3: @_sh4 ... is an issue, but I am not sure the situation warrants the kind of hopelessness and unpredictability conveyed here.
column4: @BurntOutCase To paraphrase Jonathan Haidt, this is the coddled American mind...
column5: @BurntOutCase The preamble of political opinions about masks, etc. makes me wonder if the hopelessness, as you point out, is intended to make a political point. It seems like a tactic to scare ppl into wearing masks.
column6: @_sh4 Yeah those were the elements that made me think that. BTW speaking of your contempt for epidemiologists there is something very interesting going on that they need to get into the bottom off ...
column7: @_sh4 It is not just mask compliance. I have noticed in NJ increasing socialization and crowding in public places as the state has reopened. Yet we don't detect a pickup in cases. Could it be that herd immunity can be reached at lower levels than thought or perhaps seroprevalence ...
column8: @_sh4 ... estimates are missing true infection attack rates? It is quite puzzling but I see no attempts to engage with it by epidemiologists.

column2:
Myths about the Corona Virus

1. Taking ice cream and other cold foods do not facilitate or aid the onset of the disease.
2. Taking a hot bath does not prevent the new coronavirus disease.
3. The new coronavirus CANNOT be transmitted via mosquito bites. https://t.co/RBZy4aA12F
column3: 4. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV. To protect yourself against the new coronavirus, you should frequently clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.
column4:
5. Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus.
However, they cannot detect people who are infected but are not yet sick with a fever.
column5:
5. Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus.
However, they cannot detect people who are infected but are not yet sick with a fever.
column6: This is because it takes between 2 and 10 days before people who are infected become sick and develop a fever.
column7: 6. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes (i.e. eyes, mouth). Be aware that both alcohol and chlorine can be useful to disinfect surfaces,
column8:
but they need to be used under appropriate recommendations.
7. Antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.
The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column9:
8. To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
Some specific treatments are under investigation and will be tested through clinical trials.

column2:
I. Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus ?

Antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column3:
D. How can I protect myself 
You can protect yourself by:
-  Washing your hands with soap and running water frequently : before and after eating, after using toilet, touching animals or animal waste
- Covering mouth and nose with a disposable tissue when coughing or sneezing
column4:
- Avoiding close contact with anyone who shows symptoms.
- Seek medical care if you have fever, cough or difficulty breathing.

Can eating garlic help prevent the virus?

Garlic does have antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from outbreak that garlic has protected people from the virus.

Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?
column3: common questions about covid-19 https://t.co/4lsWi6ImPq
column4:
Can an ultraviolet disinfection lamp kill the new coronavirus?

UV lamps shouldn‚Äôt be used to sterilize hands or other areas of skin as UV radiation can cause cell deaths. 

How effective are thermal scanners in detecting people infected with the new coronavirus?
column5:
Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have a fever because of infection with the virus.

They can‚Äôt detect people who are infected but are not yet sick with fever. Due to it taking between 2-10 days before people who are infected become sick and develop a fever.
column6:
Can spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body kill the new coronavirus?

No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes (i.e. eyes, mouth).
column7:
Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against the virus?

No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B vaccine, do not provide protection against the virus.

The virus is so new and different that it needs its own vaccine.
column8:
Can rinsing your nose with saline help prevent the virus?

No. There is no evidence that rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from the virus. 

There is some limited evidence that rinsing nose with saline can help people recover more quickly from the common cold.

column2:
Is COVID-19 the same as SARS?
No. The virus that causes COVID-19 and the one that caused the outbreak of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) in 2003 are related to each other genetically, but the diseases they cause are quite different.
column3:
WHAT ARE CORONAVIRUSES, COVID-19 AND HOW ARE THEY RELATED TO SARS?

What is a coronavirus?
Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans.
column4: In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS).
column5:
The most recently discovered coronavirus causes coronavirus disease COVID-19.

What is COVID-19?
COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus. This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in Dec 2019.
column6: SARS was more deadly but much less infectious than COVID-19. There have been no outbreaks of SARS anywhere in the world since 2003.

column2:
Q: Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new #coronavirus (2019-nCoV)?
A: No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.
The 2019-nC0V is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should  not be used as a means of prevention or treatment. https://t.co/F6qMz0ojoh
column6:
@WHOWPRO @WHOSEARO @WHO_Europe @pahowho @WHOEMRO @WHOAFRO Q: Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against #2019nCoV?
A: No. Vaccines against pneumonia do not provide protection against 2019-nCoV.
The virus is new and different. It needs its own vaccine.

#KnowTheFacts https://t.co/xoUz6PzHIo
column7:
@WHOWPRO @WHOSEARO @WHO_Europe @pahowho @WHOEMRO @WHOAFRO Q: Is it safe to receive a letter or a package from China?
A: Yes, it is safe. People receiving packages from China are not at risk of contracting #2019nCoV.
From previous analysis, we know coronaviruses do not survive long on objects, such as letters or packages.

#KnowTheFacts https://t.co/RBBqjkd5JQ

column2:
I'm not a medical professional but I would want to share I little I have learnt about #Coronavirus and #COVID19

What is a Coronavirus?
A coronavirus is a virus that is found in animals and, rarely, can be transmitted from animals to humans and then spread person to person.
column3:
There are 3 currently identified #coronaviruses
1.The MERS virus, or Middle East respiratory syndrome.

2. The SARS virus, or severe acute respiratory syndrome, which first occurred in the Guangdong province in southern China
3. The #COVID19 or the #WuhanCoronovirus
column4:
COVID-19 symptoms range from mild to severe. It takes 2-14 days after exposure for symptoms to develop. Symptoms may include:

1.fever 
Anyone with a measured temperature of at least 100.4 ¬∞F [38 ¬∞C]) 
2. Cough
3. Shortness of breath
column5:
There is currently no vaccine or treatment for COVID-19. Symptoms of a coronavirus usually go away on their own. If symptoms feel worse than a common cold, contact your doctor to prescribe pain or fever medication.
As with a cold or the flu, drink fluids and get plenty of rest.

column2:
HOW DOES COVID-19 SPREAD?

ü§ß People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. 

üí¶ The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales.
column3:
ü•Ñ These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. 

üëà Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. 

‚ÜîÔ∏è People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who
column4:
coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.

WHO is assessing ongoing research on the ways COVID-19 is spread and will continue to share updated findings.
column5:
Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?
Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.
column6:
Can COVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?
The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low.
column7:
However, many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms. This is particularly true at the early stages of the disease. It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill.  

#WHOWhatsapp

column2:
Part 3

What are the symptoms of COVID-19?

The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually. 
#FREDIBOAT
column3:
Part 5

Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. People with fever, cough and difficulty breathing should seek medical attention.

#FREDIBOAT
column4:
Part 6

How does COVID-19 spread?

People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales. 

#FREDIBOAT
column5:
Part 7

These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19
column6:
Part 8

who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.

WHO is assessing ongoing research on the ways COVID-19 is spread and will continue to share updated findings.¬†¬†¬†¬†

#FREDIBOAT
column7:
Part 9
Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?

Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.¬† See previous answer on ‚ÄúHow does COVID-19 spread?‚Äù
column8:
Part 10

Can CoVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?

The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low. However, 
#FREDIBOAT
column9:
Part 11

many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms. This is particularly true at the early stages of the disease. It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill.¬† 
#FREDIBOAT
column10:
Part 12

WHO is assessing ongoing research on the period of transmission of COVID-19 and will continue to share updated findings.¬†¬†¬†¬†
#FREDIBOAT
column11:
Part 13

Can I catch COVID-19 from the feces of someone with the disease?

The risk of catching COVID-19 from the feces of an infected person appears to be low. While initial investigations suggest the virus may be present in feces in some cases, spread through this 
#FREDIBOAT
column12:
Part 14 

route is not a main feature of the outbreak. WHO is assessing ongoing research on the ways COVID-19 is spread and will continue to share new findings. 
#FREDIBOAT
column13:
Part 15

Because this is a risk, however, it is another reason to clean hands regularly, after using the bathroom and before eating

#FREDIBOAT
column14:
Part 16

What can I do to protect myself and prevent the¬†spread of disease?

Protection measures for everyone

Stay aware of the latest information on the COVID-19 outbreak, available on the WHO website and through your national and local public health authority. 
#FREDIBOAT
column15:
Part 17

Many countries around the world have seen cases of COVID-19 and several have seen outbreaks. Authorities in China and some other countries have succeeded in slowing or stopping their outbreaks. However, the situation is unpredictable so check regularly
#FREDIBOAT
column16:
for the latest news.

Part 18
You can reduce your chances of being infected or spreading COVID-19 by taking some simple precautions:
Regularly and thoroughly clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.
Why? Washing your hands with 
#FREDIBOAT
column17:
Part 19

droplets from their nose or mouth which may contain virus. If you are too close, you can breathe in the droplets, including the COVID-19 virus if the person coughing has the disease.

Avoid touching eyes, nose and mouth.
Why? Hands touch many 
#FREDIBOAT
column18:
Part 20

surfaces and can pick up viruses. Once contaminated, hands can transfer the virus to your eyes, nose or mouth. From there, the virus can enter your body and can make you sick.

Make sure you, and the people around you, follow good respiratory hygiene. 
#FREDIBOAT
column19:
Part 21
This means covering your mouth and nose with your bent elbow or tissue when you cough or sneeze. Then dispose of the used tissue immediately.
Why? Droplets spread virus. By following good respiratory hygiene you protect the people around you from viruses such as
column20:
Part 22

cold, flu and COVID-19.

Stay home if you feel unwell. If you have a fever, cough and difficulty breathing, seek medical attention and call in advance. Follow the directions of your local health authority.
Why? National and local authorities will 
#FREDIBOAT
column21:
Part 23

have the most up to date information on the situation in your area. Calling in advance will allow your health care provider to quickly direct you to the right health facility. This will also protect you and help prevent spread of viruses and other infections.
#FREDIBOAT
column22:
Part 24

Keep up to date on the latest COVID-19 hotspots (cities or local areas where COVID-19 is spreading widely). If possible, avoid traveling to places ¬†‚Äì especially if you are an older person or have diabetes, heart or lung disease.
Why? 
#FREDIBOAT
column23:

You have a higher chance of catching COVID-19 in one of these areas.

Protection measures for persons who are in or have recently visited (past 14 days) areas where COVID-19 is spreading

Follow the guidance outlined above (Protection measures for 
#FREDIBOAT
column24:
Part 26

everyone)

Self-isolate by staying at home if you begin to feel unwell, even with mild symptoms such as headache, low grade fever (37.3 C or above) and slight runny nose, until you recover. If it is essential for you to have someone bring you supplies or 
#FREDIBOAT
column25:
Part 27

to go out, e.g. to buy food, then wear a mask to avoid infecting other people.
Why? Avoiding contact with others and visits to medical facilities will allow these facilities to operate more effectively and help protect you and others from possible COVID-19 
#FREDIBOAT
column26:

Why? Calling in advance will allow your health care provider to quickly direct you to the right health facility. This will also help to prevent possible spread of COVID-19 and other viruses.

#FREDIBOAT
column27:
Part 29

How likely am I to catch COVID-19?

The risk depends on where you ¬†are - and more specifically, whether there is a COVID-19 outbreak unfolding there.

For most people in most locations the risk of catching COVID-19 is still low. However, there are now places around
column28:
Part 30

the world (cities or areas) where the disease is spreading. For people living in, or visiting, these areas the risk of catching COVID-19 is higher. Governments and health authorities are taking vigorous action every time a new case of COVID-19 is identified. Be sure to
column29:
Part 31

comply with any local restrictions on travel, movement or large gatherings. Cooperating with disease control efforts will reduce your risk of catching or spreading COVID-19.

COVID-19 outbreaks can be contained and transmission stopped, as has been shown in

column30:

column2:
How does COVID-19 spread?
People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales.
column3:
What are the symptoms of COVID-19?
The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually. https://t.co/LM6wHFpLd9
column4: Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms and don't feel unwell. Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing.
column5: Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. People with fever, cough and difficulty breathing should seek medical attention.
column6: These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with ++
column7: COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.
column8:
Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?
Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.
Can CoVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?
column9: The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low. However, many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms.
column10: This is particularly true at the early stages of the disease. It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill.
column11:
You can reduce your chances of being infected or spreading COVID-19 by taking some simple precautions:

Regularly and thoroughly clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.
column12:
Why? Washing your hands with soap and water or using alcohol-based hand rub kills viruses that may be on your hands.
Maintain at least 1 metre (3 feet) distance between yourself and anyone who is coughing or sneezing.
Why?
column13:
When someone coughs or sneezes they spray small liquid droplets from their nose or mouth which may contain virus. If you are too close, you can breathe in the droplets, including the COVID-19 virus if the person coughing has the disease.
Avoid touching eyes, nose and mouth.
Why?
column14:
Hands touch many surfaces and can pick up viruses. Once contaminated, hands can transfer the virus to your eyes, nose or mouth. From there, the virus can enter your body and can make you sick.
Make sure you, and the people around you, follow good respiratory hygiene.
column15:
This means covering your mouth and nose with your bent elbow or tissue when you cough or sneeze. Then dispose of the used tissue immediately.
Why?
column16: Droplets spread virus. By following good respiratory hygiene you protect the people around you from viruses such as cold, flu and COVID-19. Stay home if you feel unwell. If you have a fever, cough and difficulty breathing, seek medical attention and call in advance.
column17:
Follow the directions of your local health authority.
Why? National and local authorities will have the most up to date information on the situation in your area. Calling in advance will allow your health care provider to quickly direct you to the right health facility.
column18:
This will also protect you and help prevent spread of viruses and other infections.
Keep up to date on the latest COVID-19 hotspots (cities or local areas where COVID-19 is spreading widely). If possible, avoid traveling to places ‚Äì especially if you are an older person or have++
column19:
diabetes, heart or lung disease.
Why? You have a higher chance of catching COVID-19 in one of these areas.

What are the symptoms of COVID-19?

The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually. Some ppl become 1/3

column2:
How does Covid-19 spread?
At the moment, we know that the virus is transmitted through contaminated droplets. Droplets of saliva or mucus carrying the respiratory virus can travel one to three metres through coughing or sneezing.
column3: As of today,¬†169,906¬†Covid-19 cases have been confirmed, resulting in¬†6,644¬†fatalities worldwide. After its discovery last December, in Wuhan, China, the virus started to spread around the world, causing panic.
column4:
How do the seven human
coronaviruses differ?

The main difference lies in the severity of the illnesses they cause. The first four respiratory viruses range from mild to medium, while Sars and Mers can cause respiratory illness of high severity.
column5:
How do viruses work?
A virus is a protein box with genetic material inside which needs a living cell to replicate. It enters the cell through binding with receptors and ‚Äúreprogrammes it‚Äù to make copies of itself, working as a template to replicate more viruses inside the body.
column6: The virus needs to fully enter the respiratory tract for infection to happen, but that's why the risk of infection can be reduced by avoiding close contact with sick people. Washing your hands thoroughly greatly reduces the risk of infection.
column7: There are reports that infection is possible through faeces and recirculated air ventilation systems and air conditioners. But this has not been systematically studied, so it is hard to say with 100 per cent certainty.
column8:
How deadly is the new coronavirus compared to Sars, Mers and the four coronaviruses that cause the common cold?
We cannot determine this for certain as the apparent mortality rate is likely to be overestimated at the start of an outbreak, because a lot of mild cases are missed.
column9:
Also, with Covid-19, some people can be asymptomatic - meaning the virus is not always detected and therefore not recorded.

The mortality rate for influenza is 0.1 per cent, but since Covid-19 is so new it remains to be seen just how many cases will turn out to be fatal.
column10: It is commonly cited that in a given year with no complications, influenza kills 500,000 people. Compared to the four respiratory coronaviruses, the mortality rate for Sars-Cov-2 is higher.
column11: Although compared to Sars (9.6 per cent) and Mers (34.4 per cent), Covid-19 shows a low mortality rate but with a wider spread, making the total number of deaths larger.
column12:
Can summer, or warmer temperatures help eradicate the virus?
For some respiratory viruses this does happen. Not because of the temperature, but also thanks to the humidity and changes in social patterns of human beings. In this case, it is still premature to say.

column2:
What are the symptoms of COVID-19?

√ò Cough
√ò Fever
√ò Breathing difficulties
Unwell people who have recently travelled from any country with ongoing transmission of COVID-19 ü¶†should immediately contact NCDC on 07032864444 or 0800-97000010 (toll-free).
column3:
Am I at risk of catching COVID-19 from a package or products that arrive from countries with a confirmed case(s)?

Currently there is no evidence to support transmission of COVID-19 associated with imported goods or packages countries with ongoing transmission.
column4: Till date, there is no known case of COVID-19 in Nigeria associated with imported goods.
column5:
Should I stop my children from going to school?

No. The current situation in the country does not warrant a shutdown of daily activities. During a pandemic, various measures are instituted depending on how serious the illness is and how easily it is spread from person to person.
column6: At the moment, there is one confirmed case in Nigeria. Therefore, measures such as school closure or closure of large gatherings, are not required. Persons with persistent cough or sneezing should stay home or keep a social distance, but not mix in a crowd.
column7:
Is there anything a person can do to avoid becoming infected?

To reduce the risk of infection or spread of COVID-19, members of the public are advised to adhere to the following hand and respiratory hygiene measures:
column8: ‚Ä¢ Wash your hands regularly with soap under running water and use hand sanitisers frequently
column9: ‚Ä¢ Cover your mouth and nose properly with tissue paper when sneezing and/or coughing and immediately dispose of the tissue in a covered waste bin. After this, wash your hands with soap and water or use hand sanitiser
column10: ‚Ä¢ You may also cough into your elbow if disposable tissue is not available. You are strongly advised not to re-use handkerchiefs
column11: ‚Ä¢ If you become sick while travelling, you should avoid close contact with other people while you are symptomatic and cover your mouth and nose with a face mask
column12: ‚Ä¢ Avoid close contact with anyone showing symptoms of respiratory illness such as coughing and sneezing
column13: ‚Ä¢ Healthcare workers are always advised to observe standard infection prevention and control measures when attending to patients and take a travel history
column14:
What can businesses do to protect their staff?

Businesses have an important role to play in protecting their employees. Employers are advised to circulate NCDC‚Äôs public health advisory on COVID-19 to all staff.
column15: Encourage sick employees to stay at home if they are unwell. Ensure routine cleaning of high contact areas such as toilets, door handles, telephones.
column16:
If staff have travelled to any of the countries with ongoing transmission, they should be advised to self-isolate for 14 days.

*Countries with ongoing transmission as at February 28, 2020: China, Republic of Korea, Italy, Iran, Japan

End.

column2:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing or treating the COVID-19?
No. Antibiotics dont work against viruses, they only work on bacterial infections.COVID-19 is caused by a virus, so antibiotics do not work. Antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment
column3:
Protection measures for everyone. 

* Regularly and thoroughly clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water. 
* Maintain at least 1 metre (3 feet) distance between yourself and anyone who is coughing or sneezing.
column4:
* Avoid touching eyes, nose and mouth. 
* Make sure you, and the people around you, follow good respiratory hygiene. This means covering your mouth and nose with your bent elbow or tissue when you cough or sneeze.
column5: *Stay home if you feel unwell. If you have a fever, cough and difficulty breathing, seek medical attention.
column6:
Should I wear a mask to protect myself? 

Only wear a mask if you are ill with COVID-19 symptoms (especially coughing) or looking after someone who may have COVID-19. Disposable face mask can only be used once.
column7:
The following measures ARE NOT effective against COVID-2019 and can be harmful:

Smoking
Wearing multiple masks
Taking antibiotics.  

Culled from W.H.O website
column8:
Who is at risk of developing severe illness?
COVID-2019 affects people, older persons and persons with pre-existing medical conditions (such as high blood pressure, heart disease, lung disease, cancer or diabetes)  appear to develop serious illness more often than others.

column2:
What are the symptoms of COVID-19?

The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually. 

1/3
column3:
Let¬¥s help fight the spread of the coronavirus. Let¬¥s protect ourselves, our loved ones, colleagues, friends, the community and our country. So here¬¥s a thread of Q&A on coronaviruses (COVID-19) from World Health Organization.
#CovidfreeApril
#CovidfreePhilippines
#CovidfreeWorld
column4:
What is a coronavirus?
Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans.  In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as MERS, SARS and now, COVID-19.
column5:
What is COVID-19?
COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus. This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.
column6:
Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms and don't feel unwell. Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing. 

2/3
column7:
Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. People with fever, cough and difficulty breathing should seek medical attention.

3/3
column8:
How does COVID-19 spread?

People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales. 

1/3
column9:
These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. 

2/3
column10:
People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.

3/3
column11:
Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?

Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.
column12:
Can CoVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?

The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low. 

1/2
column13:
However, many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms. This is particularly true at the early stages of the disease. It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill.  

2/2

column2:
THREAD on #COVID19 spread & testing.

How does COVID-19 spread?

It spreads through respiratory droplets from coughs and sneezes. Close contact, which is being closer than 6 feet for more than 10 minutes w/a sick individual, increases your risk of catching it. (1/12) 

#COVID19US https://t.co/phLi8f97Dw
column3:
‚Ä¶ individuals with severe illness from COVID-19 may need hospital care, which would still be supportive care of symptoms because there is no specific treatment for the disease‚Ä¶ (5/12)

#COVID19US
column4:
‚Ä¶ Whether you are positive or negative, we ask that people stay home for 72 hours after their symptoms end to avoid passing illness to others‚Ä¶ (6/12)

#COVID19US
column5:
‚Ä¶ If you test positive for COVID-19, you will need to stay home for 7 days after your positive test OR for 72 hours after your symptoms end, whichever is LONGER‚Ä¶ (7/12)

#COVID19US
column6:
‚Ä¶ This is different from flu, which has a specific antiviral medication that can be given if a flu test is positive. No specific treatment for COVID-19 = no different care after a positive test result. (8/12)

#COVID19US
column7:
Who gets tested? How?

Anyone with symptoms can go to a healthcare provider. If the provider decides a test is needed, they can collect specimens and request a test from the state lab or order one from a commercial lab‚Ä¶ (9/12)

#COVID19US
column8:
‚Ä¶ Working with a provider is very important‚Äîa cough and fever can have many causes, so seeing a provider will help you get an answer about cause and treatment‚Ä¶ (10/12)

#COVID19US
column9:
‚Ä¶ There is no specific treatment for COVID-19, so if your symptoms are from some other cause, it‚Äôs important that you‚Äôre working with a provider who can help you get well. (11/12)

column2: @SayingHello2U From WHO info page. Is COVID-19 the same as SARS? No. The virus that causes COVID-19 and the one that causes Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) are related to each other genetically, but they are different. SARS is more deadly but much less infectious than COVID-19.
column3: @sphacelate In what way? This one spreads far quicker, and it has already reached far more people than SARS did. Also, it takes 4 to 5 weeks to die, and so nobody knows the fatality death rate yet.
column4: @sphacelate Right off, his data is wrong. It started early December - not the 29th December. Also the World Health Orgaization says it's worse than SARS.
column5: @sphacelate If a disease only spreads to a thousand people, and it kills 10%, that is only a 100 dead. If a disease spreads to 5 million people, and it kills 3% (current fatality rate), it kills 30,000 people. It is the ease of spreading that makes it more dangerous.
column6: @SayingHello2U I would still put that on par with a bad flu bug, most people don't die from it and that fatality percentage can change based on how it's reacted to and where geographically you look.  With proper prevention this won't result in a pandemic.
column7: @sphacelate Yes, I know that. But it takes approximately 5 weeks from the date of manifestation of the illness (not the incubation period) to die. Most people have not recovered yet. So the death rate might be a lot higher. The fact that SARS didn't spread easily means it was less dangerous.

Are pregnant women at higher risk from COVID-19?

Ans: Research is underway to understand impacts of #COVID19 infection on #pregnant women. Data is limited; presently no evidence that they are at higher risk. #parentingQ #CoronaVirus
column3: But take precautions & report symptoms to doctor. @WHO will update more evidence @V2019N #parentingQ #CoronaVirus
column4:
Q4: Can #COVID-19 be transferred from mom to unborn/newborn?

Ans: This is still not known, if a #pregnant woman with COVID19 can pass virus to her baby during pregnancy or delivery. To date, #COVID19 has not been found in samples of amniotic fluid or breastmilk @MoHFW_INDIA @WHO
column5:
Q5: What care should be available during #pregnancy & childbirth?

Ans: All #pregnant women, including those with confirmed or suspected #COVID19 infections, have the right to high quality care before, during and after childbirth. @V2019N @MoHFW_INDIA @WHO (1/2) #parentingQ
column6: If #COVID19 is suspected or confirmed, health workers should take appropriate precautions to reduce risks of infection to themselves and others, including appropriate use of protective clothing @V2019N @MoHFW_INDIA @WHO (2/4) #parentingQ #CoronaVirus
column7:
Q6: Do #pregnantwomen wit suspected/confirmed #COVID19 need 2 give birth by caesarean section?

Ans: No. @WHO advise that C-section should only be performed when medically justified. Mode of birth should be individualized & based on a preferences & obstetric indications
column8:
Q7: Can women with #COVID19 breastfeed?

Ans: Yes. Women with COVID19 can #breastfeed if they wish to do so. They should:

- Practice respiratory hygiene during feeding, wearing a mask where available;
- Wash hands before and after touching the baby

#parentingQ #CoronaVirus
column9:

column2:
Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?

Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.
column3:
How does COVID-19 spread?

People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales.
column4: These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth.
column5: People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.
column6: World Health Organisation is assessing ongoing research on the ways COVID-19 is spread and will continue to share updated findings. https://t.co/OiusUGcg8F

column3:
E. Protecting others from getting sick 

You can protect others from getting sick taking the following precautions 
- When coughing and sneezing, cover mouth and nose with elbow or tissue
- Throw the tissue in a bin immediately after use
column4:
- Clean hands with soap after coughing or sneezing 
- Avoid close contact when you are experiencing cough and fever
- Avoid spitting in public
- Seek medical care if your loved one have fever, cough or difficulty breathing.
column5:
- Have cough, fever and difficulty breathing and seek medical care
- Do not have these symptoms you do not have to wear a mask as there is no evidence that they protect people who are not sick
column6: - Are healthy, you only need to wear a mask if you are taking care of a person with suspected CoronaVirus Infection
column7:
G. How to put on, use, take off and dispose of a mask 
‚Ä¢Before putting on a mask, clean hands with alcohol-based hand rub or soap and water.
‚Ä¢Cover mouth and nose with mask and make sure there are no gaps between your face and the mask.
column8:
‚Ä¢Avoid touching the mask while using it;
‚Ä¢Replace the mask with a new one as soon as it is damp and do not re-use single-use is advised.
column9:
H. Does the new coronavirus affect older people

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus
column10:
I. Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus ?

Antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column11: However, if you are hospitalized you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible.
column12: However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized support.

column2:
MYTH-12: DOES THE NEW CORONAVIRUS AFFECT OLDER PEOPLE, OR ARE YOUNGER PEOPLE ALSO SUSCEPTIBLE?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

14/n
column3:
MYTH-07: HOW EFFECTIVE ARE THERMAL SCANNERS IN DETECTING PEOPLE INFECTED WITH THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus. 
10/n
column4:
MYTH-08: CAN SPRAYING ALCOHOL OR CHLORINE ALL OVER YOUR BODY KILL THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes. 

11/n
column5:
MYTH-09: DO VACCINES AGAINST PNEUMONIA PROTECT YOU AGAINST THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.

12/n
column6:
MYTH-10: CAN REGULARLY RINSING YOUR NOSE WITH SALINE HELP PREVENT INFECTION WITH THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus. 

13/n
column7:
MYTH-13: ARE ANTIBIOTICS EFFECTIVE IN PREVENTING AND TREATING THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.

15/n
column8:
MYTH-14: ARE THERE ANY SPECIFIC MEDICINES TO PREVENT OR TREAT THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

Source: @WHO

16/n

column2:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column3:
Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus. https://t.co/jqJLzLRaqX
column4:
Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV). Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to
column5:
be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus.¬†

WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene. https://t.co/pmLJPjrF3f
column6: However, if you are hospitalized for the 2019-nCoV, you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible. https://t.co/5hBww654bN
column7:
Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat
column8: symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized supportive care. Some specific treatments are under investigation, and will be tested through clinical trials. WHO is helping to accelerate research and development efforts with a range or partners. https://t.co/KlV6s5lbvH

column2:
What is #herdimmunity threshold for #COVID19?
A topic of much discussion due to large uncertainty & huge consequences for long term impact. 

New paper illustrates 1 key aspect that can reduce it substantially (spoiler: we still don't know value). Thread.
https://t.co/Sgrg1yrlOq
column3:
Human populations are NOT WELL-MIXED & HOMOGENOUS, so calcs give likely upper bound. 
Q: So what is herd immunity threshold (HIT) for real pops?
A: *Usually* lower & it depends on variation among individuals in 3 things: 1) contact rates; 2) susceptibility; 3) infectiousness.
column4:
Background: If we know reproductive number R0 for pathogen in population, herd immunity threshold (HIT) for WELL-MIXED HOMOGENOUS population is simply 1-1/R0. 
(Note R0 varies w/ behavior, host traits, environment so differs over time&space).
column5:
1) If some individuals have few contacts then they are unlikely to be infected, lowering HIT. (note: variation in contacts can lead to faster early spread).
2) If some aren't susceptible to infection that reduces HIT. 
3)If some people don't transmit that also reduces HIT.
column6: Positive correlations among these traits - if individuals w/ more contacts are more susceptible and infectious - can make for very rapid changes in dynamics. Sadly not much empirical data on these correlations & limited data on predictors of variation on susc. & infect.
column7:
However, see paper by @mgmgomes1 that is even better (b/c more general, better data) than Science paper cited above. Fig shows how variation susc, contacts affects HIT, f, for R0=3; so HIT=0.66, f = 0.94.
https://t.co/P5n0c1tXK1 https://t.co/j44vxDQ9Bq
column8: Science paper (link above) also shows how reasonable variation in contact rates among individuals reduces HIT. It considers differential mixing among age groups and hypothetical variation among individuals w/in each age group having more or fewer contacts.
column9: The strange part is that it's not clear what source their age-mixing data comes from. The citation they give is NOT a published paper - it's a link to a page w/ Matlab files. It's weird because there are several age-mixing datasets out there. @sbfnk can probably provide best ones
column10: The take home of the science paper is that pops partially structured by age (i.e. NOT well-mixed) and w/ arbitrary differential "activity" (contact rates) w/in ages can reduce HIT for R0=2.5 from 0.6 to 0.43. https://t.co/z5XPjIET2e
column11: The conclusion in the abstract is appropriately worded in making it clear that the paper is simply an illustration of a concept, not an actual estimate of the most likely value. https://t.co/yYGDmGEdL5
column12: What I find puzzling is that this paper is in Science. It's a extremely simple modeling exercise, with arbitrarily chosen parameter values. It isn't as general as @mgmgomes1 paper cited above, and it's not clear it has any new empirical data. Many older papers say same thing.
column13: @mgmgomes1 paper is much better in providing empirical estimates of heterogeneity & impacts on HIT, f based on data (colored lines in figure). https://t.co/OuxCx8yw5Q
column14:
In idealized population, early vaccination to HIT will prevent outbreak b/c Rt=R0*S/N so Rt<1. However, an epidemic will overshoot HIT & infect larger fraction f of pop where f=1-exp(-(f*R0)). 
For R0=2.5 (reasonable for COVID19 in some pops), HIT=0.6, and f = 0.89.
column15:
These simple calculations & flu data are what led @mlipsitch to make early widely cited rough back of the envelope calculations that 40-70% of pop would get infected without interventions. Most articles cited the 70% 
*BUT* @mlipsitch knew that...
https://t.co/8dFlzOz4t9
column16: I'd like to see uncertainty around those estimates of heterogeneity & some are very indirect estimates, but range of values is much better than arbitrarily chosen numbers and suggest heterogeneity is substantial. But ...
column17:
Serological data from NYC suggest that either heterogeneity estimate is too large or R0 is much larger, or lockdown did nothing to stop outbreak as seroprevalence is already at overhsoot epidemic size f (~20% - I added horiz dashed line).
https://t.co/Mwn4USQ6nk https://t.co/78ozBGuYPo
column19: Unfortunately, uncertainties in variation in contact rates and susceptibility/infectiousness will prevent us from ever having precise value for HIT for 1 pop & it will vary among populations (as does R0). The take home message is want to get to HIT by vaccination NOT infection.
column20:
@DiseaseEcology Are you aware of any natural or experimental data showing significant divergence (say > 10%) from the canonical immunity threshold (aside from HIV or STIs with highly stratified risk groups)?

#COVID19
column21: @AndrewALover Yes. See link at end to interview with @mlipsitch that mentions examples that indicate that heterogeneity can be substantial.
column22: @DiseaseEcology @vcolizza did some work on this in 2007 or so also when I recall correctly: ‚Äú"A programme targeting just five per cent of the population could reduce the number of infected people to just one per cent of the scenario where no antiviral drugs were available."
column23: @guido_leenders @vcolizza This is likely true for diseases with very strong heterogeneity (i.e. a few important spreaders; heterogeneity is thought to be less so for respiratory illnesses but still substantial).
column24: @DiseaseEcology @nataliexdean Do we know yet how much immunity someone who has recovered from the virus has, how long it lasts?

Q: Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new #coronavirus (2019-nCoV)?

A: No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.
The 2019-nC0V is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should  not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.

Source: @WHO https://t.co/3Y0qUSUmRw
column4:

A: People of all ages can be infected by the virus. Older people & those with pre-existing medical conditions appear to be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill. https://t.co/lyFyUnBXUb
column5:

A: Yes, it is safe. People receiving packages from China are not at risk of contracting #2019nCoV.

Coronaviruses do not survive long on objects, such as letters or packages.

#KnowTheFacts https://t.co/JvPoR3Wamf

column2:
1/ FACT: The coronavirus disease (COVID-19) is caused by a virus. NOT by bacteria.

The virus that causes COVID-19 is in a family of viruses called Coronaviridae. Antibiotics do not work against viruses.
column3:

Some people who become ill with COVID-19 can also develop a bacterial infection as a complication. In this case, antibiotics may be recommended by a health care provider.
column4:

There is currently no licensed medication to cure COVID-19. If you have symptoms, call your health care provider or COVID-19 hotline for assistance.

column2:
Are hand dryers effective in killing the new coronavirus?
No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV. To protect yourself against the new coronavirus, you should frequently clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.
column3:
The new coronavirus CANNOT be transmitted through mosquito bites.
To date there has been no information nor evidence to suggest that the new coronavirus could be transmitted by mosquitoes.
column4:
Can an ultraviolet disinfection lamp kill the new coronavirus?
UV lamps should not be used to sterilize hands or other areas of skin as UV radiation can cause skin irritation. https://t.co/2pmp1tHJwG
column5:
How effective are thermal scanners in detecting people infected with the new coronavirus?
Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus.
column6: However, they cannot detect people who are infected but are not yet sick with fever. This is because it takes between 2 and 10 days before people who are infected become sick and develop a fever. https://t.co/KnrTczQAWn
column7:
Can spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body kill the new coronavirus?
No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body.
column8: Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes (i.e. eyes, mouth). Be aware that both alcohol and chlorine can be useful to disinfect surfaces, but they need to be used under appropriate recommendations. https://t.co/wd5VHaUFan
column9:
Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against the new coronavirus?
No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.
column10: The virus is so new and different that it needs its own vaccine. Researchers are trying to develop a vaccine against 2019-nCoV, and WHO is supporting their efforts.
column11: Although these vaccines are not effective against 2019-nCoV, vaccination against respiratory illnesses is highly recommended to protect your health. https://t.co/Qu00YqTLMP
column12:
Can regularly rinsing your nose with saline help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus.
column13: There is some limited evidence that regularly rinsing nose with saline can help people recover more quickly from the common cold. However, regularly rinsing the nose has not been shown to prevent respiratory infections. https://t.co/U63r6XI6p6
column14:
Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus. https://t.co/yaLUTNsWGV
column15:
Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?
People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column16: Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus.
column17: WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene. https://t.co/bThbxOL21K
column18:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?
No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria. The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column19: However, if you are hospitalized for the 2019-nCoV, you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible. https://t.co/WpTNgsfJMU
column20:
Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?
To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column21: However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized supportive care.
column22:
Some specific treatments are under investigation, and will be tested through clinical trials. WHO is helping to accelerate research and development efforts with a range or partners.

column2:
Covid-19 Myth Busters - A Thread

1- Cold weather and snow CANNOT kill the new coronavirus.

2- Taking a hot bath does not prevent the new coronavirus disease

3- The new coronavirus cannot be transmitted through goods manufactured in China or any country reporting COVID-19 cases
column3:
4- It CANNOT be transmitted through mosquito bites

5- Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV

6- UV disinfection lamps should not be used to sterilise hands

7- Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people with a fever¬†but cannot detect infected people
column4:
8- Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body

9- Can pets at home spread it?
Currently, there is no evidence to suggest it. However, it is always a good idea to wash your hands with soap and water.
column5:
10- Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.

11- There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline protects people from infection with 2019-nCoV
column6:
12- Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus.

13- People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column7:
14- antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column8:
15- Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

column2:
Are hand dryers effective in killing the new coronavirus?
No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV. To protect yourself against the new coronavirus, you should frequently clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.
column3:
Coronavirus disease (COVID-19) advice for the public: Myth busters 
Issa threadüëáüëáüëá
column4:
Is it safe to receive a letter or a package from China?
Yes, it is safe. People receiving packages from China are not at risk of contracting the new coronavirus. From previous analysis, we know coronaviruses do not survive long on objects, such as letters or packages. https://t.co/h8kjFn9QfU
column5:
Can pets at home spread the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV)?

At present, there is no evidence that companion animals/pets such as dogs or cats can be infected with the new coronavirus. However, it is always a good idea to wash your hands with soap and water after contact with pets.
column6:
Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against the new coronavirus?
No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.
column7: The virus is so new and different that it needs its own vaccine. Researchers are trying to develop a vaccine against 2019-nCoV. Although these vaccines are not effective against 2019-nCoV, vaccination against respiratory illnesses is highly recommended to protect your health. https://t.co/HN7yBWhYlQ
column8:
Can regularly rinsing your nose with saline help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus.
column9: There is some limited evidence that regularly rinsing nose with saline can help people recover more quickly from the common cold. However, regularly rinsing the nose has not been shown to prevent respiratory infections. https://t.co/X63kY0i8o3
column10:
Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus. https://t.co/jqJLzLRaqX
column11:
Does putting on sesame oil block the new coronavirus from entering the body?
No. Sesame oil does not kill the new coronavirus. There are some chemical disinfectants that can kill the 2019-nCoV on surfaces. These include bleach/chlorine-based disinfectants, either solvents, 75%
column12:
ethanol, peracetic acid and chloroform.
However, they have little or no impact on the virus if you put them on the skin or under your nose. It can even be dangerous to put these chemicals on your skin. https://t.co/iwcpdnCcHT
column13:
Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV). Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to
column14:
be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus.¬†

WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene. https://t.co/pmLJPjrF3f
column15:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column16: However, if you are hospitalized for the 2019-nCoV, you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible. https://t.co/5hBww654bN
column17:
Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat
column18: symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized supportive care. Some specific treatments are under investigation, and will be tested through clinical trials. WHO is helping to accelerate research and development efforts with a range or partners. https://t.co/KlV6s5lbvH
