column2:
First, what is a coronavirus? 
Ulmer: This particular strain started in Wuhan Province. It traveled from animals to humans.
She said people often are first tested for the flu and strep throat so those conditions can be ruled out first.
column3:
Panelists:
Beaumont Public Health Director Sherry Ulmer
Beaumont Emergency Management Coordinator Tim Ocnashek
BISD Assistant Superintendent of Elementary Education Anita Frank
From Beaumont Psychiatric Clinic, Jason Mensah
column4: Ulmer adds there have been no confirmed cases in Beaumont or Jefferson County.
column5:
She said she doesn't want to downplay the flu. With both viruses, the biggest concern is for older people and people whose immune systems are compromised.

"We're fortunate we have a vaccine for the flu."
"If we're familiar with it, it's less scary to us."
column6: She notes because COVID-19 is so new, there's little knowledge about what it will do and at this time no vaccine.
column7:
Ulmer says she doesn't know how many cases are in Texas, but Mensah says there are 51.

Ulmer said she knows 80 percent of people who get coronavirus will just get (essentially) the common cold.
column8:
I'm trying to get more info on this stat she's quoting. I know (thanks to #TheDaily I think) that the study that showed 80 percent of people get mild symptoms included pneumonia.

So, mild is relative here.
column9: Ulmer said she's hearing anywhere between one and two years for the timeline to develop a vaccine.
column10: She says that's why it's important to continue "tried and true" healthcare methods. Wash your hands, stay home when you're sick.
column11:
Clean services with antibacterial and antiviral sprays.

Lysol, Clorox and 409 are CDC-approved to kill the virus.

"We understand that the virus can last on surfaces for up to three hours."
column12: Feldschau asks how coronavirus is spread. He gives some facts he's heard and asks the panel to separate fact and fiction. He's been told it spreads through coughing and sneezing, lives several hours airborne and three days on hard surfaces and a person is contagious for 37 days.
column13: Ulmer reiterates that the virus lasts for three hours on hard surfaces. The virus is transmitted person-to-person. She says that can include being in close quarters with someone, simply talking to them because you can breath in the droplets.
column14: That's why six feet is the recommendation when doing social distancing.
column15: Ulmer said the health department is putting together "soemthing" so people know what the next step is if Jefferson County has a confirmed case.
column16:
(I'm going to use Tim's first name because his last name is hard to keep spelling.)
So ... Tim says the city wants to reduce the spread by taking preemptive measures. That includes limiting crowds, increasing the outreach and the encouragement of people to take precautionary 1/2
column17:
measures. 

I would like to add, as of Friday, the city had not cancelled any events that would limit crowds. The comment was at this time, danger is not high enough that that consideration needed to be taken. 2/2
column18:
Tim says "we're not trying to scare people. There's a lot of bad information out there."

He encourages people to get information only from reputable sources, instead of looking at things on Facebook or from friends and spreading it like it's a fact.
column19:
"We would encourage people to be patient because it's a fluid situation." - Feldshau

He notes that people questioned having a live audience when the panel was announced earlier this week. However when advice was given to keep events small, the church went to live streaming.
column20: Ulmer says the city nine years ago developed a pandemic plan. And several times a year, the city gets together to talk about the plans and practice them.
column21: "We are as prepared as we can be with the information we're getting. Of course it's fluid, but we're accustomed to these types of situations."
column22:
Reiterating a point made previous, people most at risk are those 65 and older and those with preexisting conditions.
She said children diagnosed with coronavirus 19 years and under are "doing very well."

"For our children it sounds like God has smiled on us."
column23:
Now talking about "flattening the curve." People are trying to take protective measures to flatten the peak of infections.

"This is not here today and gone tomorrow." -Feldschau
column24: Ulmer said allowing the infections to peak so high would "tax our healthcare system." Should the city/county get there, it would have to look at "alternative" ways to treat people. She didn't expand on what those alternatives are.
column25: She said that's one reason why people should call their doctor or emergency rooms before just showing up.
column26: "I we know that you're coming, the staff can be ready for you. They can meet you outside, they can give you a mask ... that's one way now we're trying to alleviate the workload on the healthcare system is to try to plan 1/2
column27: as best we can that people are going to be expected to coming in with complaints of difficulty breathing and thoughts of coronavirus." 2/2
column28:
Feldshau says the state of emergency is not for where we are now, but as a precaution to avoid losing control in the future.

"If we ever lose control, we're going to have a serious problem."
column29:
From comment section on the video: 
"If this virus is just like the flu & spreads like viruses do (airborne) I‚Äôm not understanding the panic & closure of so many things? What is it about this virus that we would want to close schools churches etc but we don‚Äôt do it for flu?"
column30: This seems to be one of the most liked and loved comments. Someone simply responded "yassss" and another said people don't know what to do "so they just shut everything down I guess."
column31: So even on a live stream intended to give people information and was very clear on why precautions are being taken ...

column5:

Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.

column2:
MYTH-07: HOW EFFECTIVE ARE THERMAL SCANNERS IN DETECTING PEOPLE INFECTED WITH THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus. 
10/n
column3:
MYTH-05: ARE HAND DRYERS EFFECTIVE IN KILLING THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV. #Covid_19 

8/n
column4:
MYTH-06: CAN AN ULTRAVIOLET DISINFECTION LAMP KILL THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

UV lamps should not be used to sterilize hands or other areas of skin as UV radiation can cause skin irritation. #Covid_19 

9/n
column5:
MYTH-08: CAN SPRAYING ALCOHOL OR CHLORINE ALL OVER YOUR BODY KILL THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes. 

11/n
column6:
MYTH-09: DO VACCINES AGAINST PNEUMONIA PROTECT YOU AGAINST THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.

12/n
column7:
MYTH-10: CAN REGULARLY RINSING YOUR NOSE WITH SALINE HELP PREVENT INFECTION WITH THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus. 

13/n
column8:
MYTH-12: DOES THE NEW CORONAVIRUS AFFECT OLDER PEOPLE, OR ARE YOUNGER PEOPLE ALSO SUSCEPTIBLE?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

14/n
column9:
MYTH-13: ARE ANTIBIOTICS EFFECTIVE IN PREVENTING AND TREATING THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.

15/n
column10:
MYTH-14: ARE THERE ANY SPECIFIC MEDICINES TO PREVENT OR TREAT THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

Source: @WHO

16/n

column2:
Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against the new coronavirus?
No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.
column3: The virus is so new and different that it needs its own vaccine. Researchers are trying to develop a vaccine against 2019-nCoV. Although these vaccines are not effective against 2019-nCoV, vaccination against respiratory illnesses is highly recommended to protect your health. https://t.co/HN7yBWhYlQ
column4:
Can regularly rinsing your nose with saline help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus.
column5: There is some limited evidence that regularly rinsing nose with saline can help people recover more quickly from the common cold. However, regularly rinsing the nose has not been shown to prevent respiratory infections. https://t.co/X63kY0i8o3
column6:
Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus. https://t.co/jqJLzLRaqX
column7:
Does putting on sesame oil block the new coronavirus from entering the body?
No. Sesame oil does not kill the new coronavirus. There are some chemical disinfectants that can kill the 2019-nCoV on surfaces. These include bleach/chlorine-based disinfectants, either solvents, 75%
column8:
ethanol, peracetic acid and chloroform.
However, they have little or no impact on the virus if you put them on the skin or under your nose. It can even be dangerous to put these chemicals on your skin. https://t.co/iwcpdnCcHT
column9:
Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV). Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to
column10:
be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus.¬†

WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene. https://t.co/pmLJPjrF3f
column11:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column12: However, if you are hospitalized for the 2019-nCoV, you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible. https://t.co/5hBww654bN
column13:
Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat
column14: symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized supportive care. Some specific treatments are under investigation, and will be tested through clinical trials. WHO is helping to accelerate research and development efforts with a range or partners. https://t.co/KlV6s5lbvH

column2: Questions may arise around UKAS accreditation ‚Äì do they meet ISO15189? No, but highly unlikely to achieve in such a short space of time. Is there integrated IT? In some cases. What is their role in serology? To ponder for the future.
column3: Private practice has been changing in recent years, so governance can be complicated ‚Äì there are self-employed pathologists and privately employed scientists in private practice and NHS employed-pathologists and privately employed scientists in the public‚Äìprivate joint ventures.
column4: Regulation and accreditation in the NHS is broad and thorough. It is mirrored, though, across the private sector ‚Äì CQC, GMC, HCPC, UKAS, NHSBT, SHOT and EQA. The regulatory burden is shared.
column5: Global shortages make procurement a dog-eat-dog world. Related pressures also meant that testing restrictions were in place. New programmes needed to be developed: lighthouse labs and the Francis Crick Institute are two great examples.
column6: QA layers for field labs: UK NEQAS, UKAS visits and visit check list: e.g. operational management, staffing, BCT, liability and indemnity, SOPs, trouble shooting, training, competencies, IQC, EQA, validation, transport, follow-up, sample and specimen reception, PPE and on and on
column7:
Now running through community testing example of Brent and Harrow CCG. Service setup within a week of formal request and another CCG seeking the service. 

But, misunderstanding remains ‚Äì 'Why can't it be like IKEA?' Understanding of labs and services needs to be more widespread.

column2:
How does COVID-19 spread?

Initially, experts believe the virus started out in animals in Wuhan, China; and was then transmitted to humans. The current version of the SARS-CoV-2 spreads from person-to-person, similar to the flu. This usually happens when a sick person coughs or
column3:
What is COVID19?

Coronaviruses are important human and animal pathogens. They have been known to cause a variety of disorders in humans, from the common cold to the more severe Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS-CoV) and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS-CoV).
column4:
In December 2019, a novel coronavirus was identified in emerging clusters of pneumonia (lung infection) cases in Wuhan, China.
The virus was previously termed ‚ÄúnCoV-2019‚Äù. At the beginning of 2020, the virus was officially named SARS-CoV-2, due to its similarities to the previous
column5: SARS-CoV. The disease, as a whole, was then officially termed by the WHO as Coronavirus Disease 2019, or ‚ÄúCOVID-19‚Äù.
column6: sneezes near other people, or when a person is in close contact with a sick person (within about 6 feet or 2 meters).
column7:
What are the symptoms of COVID-19?

Symptoms usually start a few days after a person is infected with the virus. But in some people, it can take even longer for symptoms to appear, thus the symptoms can appear anywhere between 2 to 14 days after exposure. Symptoms can include:
column8:
‚Ä¢ Fever
‚Ä¢ Cough
‚Ä¢ Trouble breathing ‚Ä¢ Feeling tired
‚Ä¢ Muscle aches
Most people have mild symptoms. Some people have no symptoms at all. But in other people, COVID-19 can lead to serious problems like pneumonia, not getting enough oxygen, or even death.
column9: This is more common in people who are older or have other health problems.
column10:
When should I see a doctor?

If you have a fever, cough, or trouble breathing and might have been exposed to COVID-19, call 937 (The Saudi MOH Service Center) immediately.
You might have been exposed if either of the following happened within the last 14 days:
column11: ‚Ä¢ You lived in, or traveled to, an area where lots of people have the virus ‚Äì the United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) has information about which areas are affected. This can be found on their website: https://t.co/dGZNsC4CO8 ncov/travelers/index.html
column12:
‚Ä¢ You had close contact with a person who has the virus ‚Äì This generally means being within about 6 feet of the person.
If your symptoms are not severe, it is best to call your doctor, nurse, or clinic before you go in. They can tell you what to do and where to go.
column13:
If you do need to go to the clinic or hospital, you will need to put on a face mask. The staff might also have you wait someplace away from other people.
If you are severely ill and need to go to the clinic or hospital right away, you should still call ahead.
column14: This way the staff can care for you while taking steps to protect others.
column15:
How is COVID-19 treated?

Most people with COVID-19 have only mild illness and can rest at home until they get better. If you have a more severe illness, you might need to stay in the hospital, possibly in the intensive care unit (also called the "ICU").
column16: There is no specific treatment for the infection, but the doctors and nurses in the hospital can monitor and support your breathing and other body functions; and make you as comfortable as possible, this is done through multiple ways, including external oxygen
column17: (e.g. oxygen mask), a ventilator (a machine that helps you breathe), and/or medication.
column18:
Can COVID-19 be prevented?

There are things you can do to reduce your chances of getting COVID-19:
‚Ä¢ Wash your hands with soap and water often. Wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 seconds, especially after blowing your nose, coughing, or sneezing; going to
column19:
the bathroom; and before eating or preparing food.
o If soap and water are not readily available, use an alcohol-based hand sanitizer with at least 60% alcohol, covering all surfaces of your hands and rubbing them together until they feel dry.
column20:
‚Ä¢ Avoid touching your face (including your eyes, mouth, and nose) with your hands
‚Ä¢ Cover your cough or sneeze with a tissue, then throw the tissue in the trash, and wash your
hands immediately after (as specified above).
‚Ä¢ Clean and disinfect frequently touched objects and
column21:
surfaces using a regular household cleaning spray or wipe.
‚Ä¢ CDC does not recommend that people who are well and healthy wear a facemask to protect themselves from respiratory diseases, including COVID-19.
o Facemasks should be used by people who show symptoms of COVID-19 to
column22:
help prevent the spread of the disease to others. The use of facemasks is also crucial for health workers and people who are taking care of someone who has COVID-19.
‚Ä¢ Stay home when you are sick, and call your doctor if you think you have been exposed to COVID- 19.
column23:
‚Ä¢ Try to stay away from people who have any symptoms of the infection.
‚Ä¢ Some experts recommend avoiding travel to certain countries where there are a lot of cases of COVID-19.

If someone in your home has COVID-19, there are additional things you can do to protect yourself:
column24:
‚Ä¢ Keep the sick person away from others ‚Äì The sick person should stay in a separate room and use a separate bathroom if possible.
‚Ä¢ Use face masks ‚Äì The sick person should wear a face mask when they are in the same room as other people. If you are caring for the sick person,
column25:
you can also protect yourself by wearing a face mask when you are in the room. This is especially important if the sick person cannot wear a mask.
‚Ä¢ Be extra careful around body fluids ‚Äì If you will be in contact with the sick person's blood, mucus, or other body fluids, wear a
column26:
disposable face mask, gown, and gloves. If any bodily fluids touch your skin, wash your hands with soap right away.
‚Ä¢ Clean often ‚Äì It's especially important to clean things that are touched a lot. This includes counters, bedside tables, doorknobs, computers, phones, tablets,
column27:
and bathroom surfaces. Also, clean any surfaces that may have blood, stool, or body fluids on them.
‚Ä¢ Wash hands ‚Äì Wash your hands with soap and water often (as specified above)
‚Ä¢ You should not share dishes, drinking glasses, cups, eating utensils, towels, or bedding with
column28:
other people or pets in your home. There is not yet a vaccine to prevent COVID-19.
How can I prepare for a possible outbreak?
It is hard to predict where future outbreaks might happen. The best thing you can do to stay healthy is to wash your hands regularly, avoid close contact
column29:
with people who are sick, and stay home if you are sick.
If there is an outbreak in your area, schools or businesses might close temporarily. If this happens, or if someone in your family gets sick with COVID-19, you might need to stay at home for a period of time.
column30: There are things you can do to prepare for this. For example, you might be able to ask your employer if you can work from home, or take time off, if it becomes necessary. You can also make sure you have a way to get in touch with relatives, neighbors, and others in your area.
column31:
This way you will be able to receive and share information easily.
If you or others in your family are anxious about COVID-19, keep in mind that most people do not get severely ill or die from it. While it helps to be prepared, and there are things you can do to lower your risk.
column32:
Where can I learn more?

As we learn more about this virus, expert recommendations will continue to change. Check with your doctor or public health official to get the most updated information about how to protect yourself.
You can also find more information about COVID-19 at the

column2:
#Coronavirus Myths You Mustn't believe
RT to save someone 

1. Hand dryers kill coronavirus

Hand dryers do not kill coronavirus. The best way to protect yourself and others from the virus is to wash your hands with soap and water or an alcohol-based hand rub.
column3:
2. Only older adults and young people are at risk

COVID-19, like other coronaviruses, can infect people of any age. However, older adults or individuals with preexisting health conditions, such as diabetes or asthma, are more likely to become severely ill.
column4:
3. Everyone with COVID-19 dies

COVID-19 is only fatal for a small percentage of people.

In a recent report, the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention concluded that 80.9% of COVID-19 cases were mild.

column2:
Exposing yourself to the sun or to temperatures higher than 25C degrees DOES NOT prevent the coronavirus disease (COVID-19)

You can catch COVID-19, no matter how sunny or hot the weather is. Countries with hot weather have reported cases of COVID-19.
column3: covid-19 myths vs truth https://t.co/QmasHPlOlL
column4:
You can recover from the coronavirus disease (COVID-19). Catching covid-19 DOES NOT mean you will have it for life.

Most of the people who catch COVID-19 can recover and eliminate the virus from their bodies. If you catch the disease, make sure you treat your symptoms.
column5:
Being able to hold your breath for 10 seconds or more without coughing or feeling discomfort DOES NOT mean you are free from the COVID-19 or any other lung disease.

The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are dry cough, tiredness and fever. Take an official test to confirm.
column6:
Drinking alcohol does not protect you against COVID-19 and can be dangerous

Frequent or excessive alcohol consumption can increase your risk of health problems and can in fact damage your immune system- which helps fight against the virus.
column7:
COVID-19 virus can be transmitted in areas with hot and humid climates

From the evidence so far, the COVID-19 virus can be transmitted in ALL AREAS, including areas with hot and humid weather. Regardless of climate, adopt protective measures when leaving the house for essentials
column8:
Cold weather and snow CANNOT kill the new coronavirus.

There is no reason to believe that cold weather can kill the new coronavirus or other diseases. The normal human body temperature remains around 36.5¬∞C to 37¬∞C, regardless of the external temperature or weather.
column9:
Taking a hot bath does not prevent the virus
Taking a hot bath will not prevent you from catching COVID-19. Your body temperature is 36.5¬∞C to 37¬∞C, regardless of the temperature of your bath or shower. Taking a hot bath with extremely hot water can be harmful, as it can burn you
column10:
The new coronavirus CANNOT be transmitted through mosquito bites.

To date there has been no information nor evidence to suggest that the new coronavirus could be transmitted by mosquitoes.  The coronavirus is a respiratory virus which spreads primarily through droplets.

No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes. 

11/n
column4:
MYTH-09: DO VACCINES AGAINST PNEUMONIA PROTECT YOU AGAINST THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.

12/n
column5:
MYTH-10: CAN REGULARLY RINSING YOUR NOSE WITH SALINE HELP PREVENT INFECTION WITH THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus. 

13/n
column6:
MYTH-12: DOES THE NEW CORONAVIRUS AFFECT OLDER PEOPLE, OR ARE YOUNGER PEOPLE ALSO SUSCEPTIBLE?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

14/n
column7:
MYTH-14: ARE THERE ANY SPECIFIC MEDICINES TO PREVENT OR TREAT THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

Source: @WHO

16/n

column2: Brain teaser: Assume that 5% of the population has #COVID19 antibodies, and the serology test has a 95% accuracy (specificity=sensitivity=0.95). What is the probability p that I have antibodies if I test positive? (For bonus points explain your answer in comments)
column3: @srchvrs Not needed to respond the teaser.
column4: @joelgrus @xamat hence the answer is the "tricky" d) (which I did not get, because I wasn't watching for strict inequalities and thought I was picking "greater than or equal to 50 but less than 95")
column5: @xamat 0.5 if you are a frequentist. If you are an hypochondriac Bayesian and you work in an hospital with COVID-19 patients, i.e., p(antibodies) > 0.05, then the probability shifts towards 1.
column6: @albertlumbreras If you apply Bayes you get the same result. Of course, things change if you change the prior, but that is unrelated to frequentist vs. bayesian.
column7: @xamat Hint: Thomas Bayes would be of great help
column8: @xamat Strict inequalities.
column9: @xamat Prior and likelihood neutralize each other exactly
column10: @xamat P(covid=Y)=0.05 P(test=Y)=0.095 P(test=Y|covid=Y)=0.95
column11: @xamat P(Covid=Y|test=Y)= P(test=Y|covid=Y) P(covid=Y) / P(test=Y) ; 0.95 0.05 / 0.095 = 0.5
column12: @xamat I'm taking my chance and not reading the other replies beforehand. It's 50/50! üò± We have two random binary variables: TST (good test) and ATB (antibodies present). Plus one observable: RES(ult). Given same specificity and sensitivity, we can assume both vars are independent (?)
column13: @xamat Thus, among four possible combinations of TST x ATB, we have two that lead to RES=positive, i.e., (TST and ATB) or (not TST and not ATB). P(TST,ATB)=P(not TST,not ATB)=0.0475. So, 50/50 between these two possibilities.
column14: @xamat 50% https://t.co/YXKgAtfUSm
column15: @xamat 400 person trial. 20 are positive. 380 negative. 361/380 of the negative test negative. 19/20 of the positive test positive.  But 19/380 negative test positive. Any positive test is 50/50 a true positive or false negative.
column16: @xamat If I test positive I am either a FP or a TP. The number of FPs is the number of negatives (95% of pop.) x the chance of misclassifying them (5%). The number of TPs is the number of positives (5% of the pop.) x the chance of correctly classifying them (95%). Hence, p=0.5.
column17: @xamat Cheeky answer categories! I'm always entertained by how similar Bayes' theorem and base rate neglect have similar names and are related to each other.
column18: @xamat 50% https://t.co/UHFkwXiQvR
column19: @xamat One of my first go-to questions while interviewing data science candidates

column2:
Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?
To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column3: Although these vaccines are not effective against 2019-nCoV, vaccination against respiratory illnesses is highly recommended to protect your health. https://t.co/Qu00YqTLMP
column4:
Can regularly rinsing your nose with saline help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus.
column5:
Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus. https://t.co/yaLUTNsWGV
column6:
Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?
People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column7: Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus.
column8: WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene. https://t.co/bThbxOL21K
column9:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?
No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria. The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column10: However, if you are hospitalized for the 2019-nCoV, you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible. https://t.co/WpTNgsfJMU
column11: However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized supportive care.
column12:
Some specific treatments are under investigation, and will be tested through clinical trials. WHO is helping to accelerate research and development efforts with a range or partners.
Pls Don't panic people with fake news because it's not real 
All Facts are in these threads https://t.co/znoHarhr06

ACWR in runners:
New, small study (n=23) of 24 months, finds:
‚Ä¢ a fortnightly low increase in the A:C workload RATIO has a higher RR of injury
‚Ä¢ acute or chronic workloads in ISOLATION were not associated with injury

column2:
How does COVID-19 spread?
People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales.
column3: Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans. ¬†In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS)
column4: and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS). The most recently discovered coronavirus causes coronavirus disease COVID-19.
column5: What is COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus. This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.
column6:
Symptoms 
The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually.
column7: Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms and don't feel unwell.Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing.
column8: Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. People with fever, cough and difficulty breathing should seek medical attention.
column9: These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. People can also catch COVID-19 if they
column10: eyes, nose or mouth. People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.
column11:
Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?

Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.¬† See previous answer on ‚ÄúHow does COVID-19 spread?‚Äù

column3: Epistemologists: if a theory of knowledge can‚Äôt account for the non-instrumental, final value of knowledge [i.e answer the tertiary value problem] the value problem for knowledge is left unsolved
column4:
@cecilymwhiteley I think knowledge itself lacks value, apart from its relation to other things it entails (like true belief). Which option is that?

Maybe the problem is left unsolved, or maybe it‚Äôs trivially solved in some sense ‚Äì unsure what to say here.
column5: @neilsinhababu Third option: there is no value problem!
column6:
@cecilymwhiteley @leelkin If knowledge lacks value, that doesn't mean the concept of knowledge lacks value. If rocks lack value, the concept of rocks may still be worth retaining.

"Knowledge" may be a useful descriptive term to pick out a class of beliefs, regardless of the value of knowledge.

column2:
What is a novel coronavirus?

A novel coronavirus (CoV) is a new strain of coronavirus that has not been previously identified in humans.
column3:
What is Coronavirus?
Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses that are known to cause illness ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS). https://t.co/siDjYJbeHJ
column4:
Can humans become infected with a novel coronavirus of animal source?

Detailed investigations found that SARS-CoV was transmitted from civet cats to humans in China in 2002 and MERS-CoV from dromedary camels to humans in Saudi Arabia in 2012.
column5: Several known coronaviruses are circulating in animals that have not yet infected humans. ¬†As surveillance improves around the world, more coronaviruses are likely to be identified.
column6:
What are the symptoms of someone infected 

It depends on the virus, but common signs include respiratory symptoms, fever, cough, shortness of breath, and breathing difficulties. In more severe cases, infection can cause pneumonia, severe acute respiratory syndrome
column7:
Can coronaviruses be transmitted from person to person?

Yes, some coronaviruses can be transmitted from person to person, usually after close contact with an infected patient, for example, in a household workplace, or health care centre
column8:
Is there a vaccine for a novel coronavirus?

When a disease is new, there is no vaccine until one is developed. It can take a number of years for a new vaccine to be developed
column9:
What can I do to protect myself?

Standard recommendations to reduce exposure to and transmission of a range of illnesses include maintaining basic hand and respiratory hygiene, and safe food practices ¬†and avoiding close contact, when possible, with anyone showing symptoms.
column10:
of respiratory illness such as coughing and sneezing

Are health workers at risk from a novel coronavirus?

Yes, they can be, as health care workers come into contact with patients more often than the general public.

column2:
What is a coronavirus?
Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans.  In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as MERS, SARS and now, COVID-19.
column3:
What are the symptoms of COVID-19?

The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually. 

1/3
column4:
Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms and don't feel unwell. Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing. 

2/3
column5:
Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. People with fever, cough and difficulty breathing should seek medical attention.

3/3
column6:
How does COVID-19 spread?

People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales. 

1/3
column7:
These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. 

2/3
column8:
People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.

3/3
column9:
Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?

Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.
column10:
Can CoVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?

The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low. 

1/2
column11:
However, many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms. This is particularly true at the early stages of the disease. It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill.  

2/2

Q's 1-17

Q1: What is COVID-19?
A1: It is the acronym for coronavirus disease 2019 caused by SARS-COV-2.

Q2: What is SARS-COV-2?
A2: It is the acronym for severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2, a virus.
column3: It has been an honour working with  Prof Bhaswati Patnaik (Psy) and Prof Navaneeta Rath (Soc) on this FAQ wrt Serological Antibody Test in @bmcbbsr for #COVID19 @HealthCheck_in @IndiaSpend @WHO @ICMRDELHI @utkaluniv01 @NCDS_BBSR @HFWOdisha @IPR_Odisha https://t.co/DFZ08n9FiP
column4:
Q3: What is serological antibody test in the context of COVID-19 or SARS-COV-2?
A3: Blood is taken from the veins and the serum/plasma put to a test to know whether the person has developed antibodies against the virus, SARS-COV-2, for the disease, COVID-19.
column5:
Q4: How long it takes to give the result of the serological antibody test?
A4: It takes 15-30 minutes to get the result of the test. So, it is a rapid diagnostic test (RDT).
column6:
Q5: Who would have developed antibodies against SARS-COV-2/COVID-19?
 A5: Only people who were infected by SARS-COV-2 and had the disease COVID-19 are likely to have developed antibodies against SARS-COV-2/COVID-19.
column7:
Q6: Why is the test conducted on population who are not known to have COVID-19?
A6: Some people might have been infected but were either asymptomatic or were with symptoms but have not been tested. Hence, the test is conducted on population who are not known to have it.
column8:
Q7:  Why the test has been initiated in Bhubaneswar, not in other cities of Odisha?
A7: As Bhubaneswar has been declared as a hotspot and there is likelihood for the rapid spread in the city and from the city to other cities, the test has been initiated in Bhubaneswar.
column9:
Q8: What is the purpose of the test?
A8:  The purpose of the test is to help in disease surveillance. It will help us arrive at an estimate of how many people from different categories of population in Bhubaneswar that might have been affected.
column10:
Q9:  Apart from random sampling for testing the population, who else can go for the antibody test?
A9: Samples of people with Severe Acute Respiratory Infections (SARI) and Influenza like Illness (ILI) are also being collected apart from random sampling of asymptomatic people.
column11:
Q10: Who will identify the population and design the sample to be tested?
A10: The Bhubaneswar Municipal Corporation (BMC) through experts from the health department have developed protocols for identifying population from among whom the sample is to be drawn for testing.
column12:
Q11: What will happen if the antibody test comes positive?
A11: If the antibody test comes positive, the person‚Äôs swab samples may be sent for RT-PCR test. This is another confirmatory test to know whether the person is currently suffering from COVID-19.
column13:
Q.12: Will serological antibody test help identify a person suffering from COVID-19?
A12: No, as per current practise and guidelines from @WHO & @ICMRDELHI, COVID-19 +ve cases are to be identified through RT-PCR in designated laboratories/testing centres.
column14:
Q13: Will identifying people who have developed antibodies be helpful in treatment for those who are suffering from COVID-19?
A13:  An independent research protocol has to be developed where plasma from those who developed antibodies can be used to treat patients.
column15:
Q14: Will those identified with antibodies for COVID-19 be immune from the disease?
A14: Further research with people who have already developed antibodies will be required.
column16:
Q.15: Whom should the residents of the city contact for the test?
A15: The residents of the city may contact their respective RWA (Resident Welfare Association), Auxiliary Nurse Midwives (ANMs), Accredited Social Health Activist (ASHA) or ward officer for the test.
column17:
Q16: Where from these rapid kits have come to the state?
A16: These rapid kits have been procured by @ICMRDELHI and have been supplied to Odisha.

column2:
1. Is it safe to receive a letter or a package from China?

Yes, it is safe. People receiving packages from China are not at risk of contracting the new coronavirus. From previous analysis, we know coronaviruses do not survive long on objects, such as letters or packages.
column3:
The #coronavirus threat is still out there and with it comes the possibility of some misconceptions, especially those fake WhatsApp broadcasts.

Here are some myths that have cropped up so far and facts by the @WHO to debunk them. https://t.co/uaDccxnsAZ
column4:
2. Can spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body kill the new coronavirus?

No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine on your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. Rather, spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes (eyes, mouth).
column5:
3. How effective are thermal scanners in detecting people infected with the new coronavirus?

Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever because of infection. However, they cannot detect people who are infected but are not yet sick with fever.
column6:
4. Can an ultraviolet disinfection lamp kill the new coronavirus?

UV lamps should not be used to sterilize hands or other areas of skin as UV radiation can cause skin irritation.
column7:
5. Are hand dryers effective in killing the new coronavirus?

No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the new coronavirus. To protect yourself against the new coronavirus, you should frequently clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap & water.
column8:
6. Can pets at home spread the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV)?

At present, there is no evidence that companion animals/pets such as dogs or cats can be infected with the new coronavirus. However, it is always a good idea to wash your hands with soap & water after contact with pets.
column9:
7. Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against the new coronavirus?

No. Vaccines against pneumonia offer no protection against the new coronavirus. The virus is so new and different that it needs its own vaccine. Researchers are trying to develop one & WHO is in support.
column10:
8. Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus but older people & those with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, etc.) appear to be more vulnerable.
column11: WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene.
column12:
9. Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column13:
10. Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus.

However, those infected with the virus are receiving appropriate care to relieve and treat symptoms.

column3: Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus.

No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV. To protect yourself against the new coronavirus, you should frequently clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.

Why is #COVI19 called a Pandemic and How does COVID 19 spread @Ovdiasis ?¬†

@WHO @NCDCgov
column3: Good morning everybody...in light of the recent influx of false information about the COVID-19 virus, we have decided as a hub to hold a live tweet chat with our distinguished medical professional @Ovdiasis to shared more light on this issue and answer any questions  you have https://t.co/z02qpXBuIm
column4:
Our guest , Dr Nyeche Ovundah is a renowned Medical practitioner at the Rivers State Teaching Hospital.

He is a Resident at the Internal Medicine Department.

Welcome @Ovdiasis .

#COVID19 https://t.co/SFveYiwEdZ
column5:
Hello @Ovdiasis!

Over the weeks now, a condition #COVID19 has had rising attention on the media, what is COVID 19?
column6:
What symptoms will an individual infected with COVID19 present with @Ovdiasis?

How long does it take from infection to presentation of symptoms of COVID 19 and how long can one be contagious?
column7:
As a Hub, with the healthy state of people at heart @Ovdiasis, we are also a bit curious about how best can one protect him or herself with the recent outbreak.

Is there any known treatment for COVID19?
column8:
Could you please tell us the difference between Self isolation and Quarantine and why is it important we maintain social/physical distance during this COVID19 period?

Please shed more light on how can we protect our loved ones from getting infected when self-isolating @Ovdiasis
column10:
Fo clarity sake @Ovdiasis, what is the criteria for COVID19 testing in Nigeria?

What centers in Nigeria can carry out COVID 19 testing? Is the testing free and what is the estimated waiting time for results?
column11:
Do you think the measures taken by the Rivers State Government to enforce isolation and prohibition of public gatherings in order to contain the spread of the virus is enough @Ovdiasis?

What lessons can be applied from the response to Ebola outbreak, to combat COVID19 outbreak?
column12:
As a Medical practitioner @Ovdiasis, what suggestions do you have to improve our Preparedness/response to COVID19?

How can Civil Society, Academia, Government, the Private sector and the general public work together to stem the Outbreak of COVID19 in Rivers State?
column13:
Dr @Ovdiasis, How do you assess the implementation of the preventive measures taken so far by the RVSG?

Do you feel the 23 LGA's in Rivers would be adequately catered for in case of an outbreak of COVID19 in the state?
column14:
In your own understanding as a Heathcare Professional, Dr @Ovdiasis, what supplies are most important to be gotten and kept during this pandemic period?

 If someone absolutely has to go out, what should he/she do?
column15:
What should one do if they experience symptoms and can't get help through Govt Hospitals/no isolation centres in their state  @Ovdiasis?

What practical steps can be taken to protect the vulnerable groups like people with underlying medical issues/ immune compromised individuals?
column16:
In rounding up Dr @Ovdiasis, what is the protocol if i suspect i have COVID 19 in Rivers state?

What is the National and Rivers State COVID 19 emergency help lines?
column17:
It's been an amazing and insightful  conversation Dr @Ovdiasis and I must confess we have learnt so much.

In conclusion, how can the Port Harcourt Global Shapers Community better contribute to the response to COVID19?
column18:
Thank you so much @Ovdiasis. We do not take for granted the time you have spent teaching us. 

We know a lot of our followers have questions to ask, please join us for a telegram discourse as regards COVID19 with our Guest Dr Ovundah by 8pm today.

https://t.co/HwltJsV8sh https://t.co/V078ONGLVX
column19: @phglobalshapers @WHO @NCDCgov It is called a pandemic because this previously unknown disease has spread from a particular locality to all over the world... A pandemic is a disease outbreak that has spread over several countries or continents... Another popular disease that is a pandemic is HIV/AIDS.

column2:
9. SARS-CoV-2 is just a mutated form of the common cold
All Coronaviruses belong to family of coronoviridae and have surface spike proteins that help them invade host, which can be humans/animals. Covid19 is thought to be passed from animals/poultry to humans.
column3:
Thread about some popular myths on corona virus

1. Spraying chlorine or alcohol on skin kills viruses in the body
Applying alcohol or chlorine to the body can cause more harm. Disinfect surfaces not skin

These cannot kill viruses within the body!!
column4:
2. Older people (>60) and young (<14) are at risk
SARS-CoV-2, like other coronaviruses, can infect people of any age. However, ANYONE with preexisting health conditions, like cancer, diabetes, lung infections, immunodeficiency is likely to get affected.
column5:
6. Cats and dogs spread coronavirus
Currently, very little evidence. However, in Hong Kong, a Pomeranian whose owner had COVID-19 became infected. The dog did not display any symptoms and this leads to an imp ques to differentiate infection from virus

https://t.co/speJA9BUHu
column6:
7. Face masks protect against coronavirus
Disposable face masks may not provide protection. Yes it is better than nothing but most masks dont fit properly, droplets can still enter the mouth and nose. Thus viral particles can also enter.
https://t.co/lLm6zXNowa
column7:
8. Hand dryers kill coronavirus
Hand dryers DONT KILL. Only soap and water is the best way followed by alcohol based sanitizers to protect oneself

column9:

Antibiotics only kill bacteria AND NOT  viruses.
column10:

Thermal scanners can detect only fever that can be caused by many reasons

column2: @JOBEEHUSTLER i@MiFraseRealidad y

Can regularly rinsing your nose with saline help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?

 No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus.
column3: There are lots of other reasons for good hygiene around pets, though. Some common bacteria can pass between animals and people, such as E.coli and Salmonella. Washing your hands with soap and water can guard against them.
column4:
Who is most at risk?

In the 2002-2003 SARS outbreak, 8,422 people were infected and there were 916 deaths worldwide. The overall death rate for infected people was 11%. But for infected people 24 and younger, the death rate was just 1%, while¬†for those aged 65+ it was 55%.
column5: In short, anyone can catch a virus. But the effect it will have on you, and how seriously ill you might become, can be dependent on several other factors.
column6: Older people and anyone with¬†pre-existing medical conditions, like asthma, diabetes or heart disease, appear to be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the new coronavirus, according to the WHO.
column7: There is some limited evidence that regularly rinsing nose with saline can help people recover more quickly from the common cold. However, regularly rinsing the nose has not been shown to prevent respiratory infections.
column8:
Can gargling mouthwash protect you from infection with the new coronavirus?

 No. There is no evidence that using mouthwash will protect you from infection with the new coronavirus.
column9: Some brands or mouthwash can eliminate certain microbes for a few minutes in the saliva in your mouth. However, this does not mean they protect you from 2019-nCoV infection.
column10:
The World Health Organization recommends taking the following precautions:

1. Frequently clean hands by using alcohol-based hand rub or soap and water
column11: 2. When coughing and sneezing cover mouth and nose with flexed elbow or tissue ‚Äì throw tissue away immediately and wash hands
column12:
3. Avoid close contact with anyone who has fever and cough

4. If you have fever, cough and difficulty breathing seek medical care early and share previous travel history with your healthcare provider
column13: 5. When visiting live markets in areas currently experiencing cases of novel coronavirus, avoid direct unprotected contact with live animals and surfaces in contact with animals
column14: 6. The consumption of raw or undercooked animal products should be avoided. Raw meat, milk or animal organs should be handled with care, to avoid cross-contamination with uncooked foods, as per good food safety practices.

*Is COVID-19 the same as SARS?*

No. The virus that causes COVID-19 and the one that caused the outbreak of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) in 2003 are related to each other genetically, but the diseases they cause are quite different. own
column3:

1 What are coronaviruses, what is COVID-19 and how is it related to SARS?

*What is a coronavirus?*

Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans.
column4: In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases such as Middle East Respiratory Syndrome (MERS) and Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS).
column5:
The most recently discovered coronavirus causes coronavirus disease COVID-19.

*What is COVID-19?

COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus. This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in December
column6:
SARS was more deadly but much less infectious than COVID-19. There have been no outbreaks of SARS anywhere in the world since 2003.

column2:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?
No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria. The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column3: Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes (i.e. eyes, mouth). Be aware that both alcohol and chlorine can be useful to disinfect surfaces, but they need to be used under appropriate recommendations. https://t.co/wd5VHaUFan
column4:
Can eating garlic help prevent infection with the new coronavirus?
Garlic is a healthy food that may have some antimicrobial properties. However, there is no evidence from the current outbreak that eating garlic has protected people from the new coronavirus. https://t.co/yaLUTNsWGV
column5:
Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?
People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column6: Older people, and people with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, heart disease) appear to be more vulnerable to becoming severely ill with the virus.
column7: WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene. https://t.co/bThbxOL21K
column8: However, if you are hospitalized for the 2019-nCoV, you may receive antibiotics because bacterial co-infection is possible. https://t.co/WpTNgsfJMU
column9:
Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?
To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).
column10: However, those infected with the virus should receive appropriate care to relieve and treat symptoms, and those with severe illness should receive optimized supportive care.
column11:
Some specific treatments are under investigation, and will be tested through clinical trials. WHO is helping to accelerate research and development efforts with a range or partners.

column2:
MYTH-05: ARE HAND DRYERS EFFECTIVE IN KILLING THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the 2019-nCoV. #Covid_19 

8/n
column3:
Actually, taking a hot bath with extremely hot water can be harmful, as it can burn you. The best way to protect yourself against COVID-19 is by frequently cleaning your hands. By doing this you eliminate viruses that may be on your hands and avoid infection. #Covid_19 

6/n
column4:
MYTH-04: THE NEW CORONAVIRUS CAN BE TRANSMITTED THROUGH MOSQUITO BITES.

To date,there has been no information nor evidence to suggest that the new coronavirus could be transmitted by mosquitoes.

7/n
column5:
MYTH-06: CAN AN ULTRAVIOLET DISINFECTION LAMP KILL THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

UV lamps should not be used to sterilize hands or other areas of skin as UV radiation can cause skin irritation. #Covid_19 

9/n
column6:
MYTH-07: HOW EFFECTIVE ARE THERMAL SCANNERS IN DETECTING PEOPLE INFECTED WITH THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever (i.e. have a higher than normal body temperature) because of infection with the new coronavirus. 
10/n
column7:
MYTH-08: CAN SPRAYING ALCOHOL OR CHLORINE ALL OVER YOUR BODY KILL THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. Spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes. 

11/n
column8:
MYTH-09: DO VACCINES AGAINST PNEUMONIA PROTECT YOU AGAINST THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. Vaccines against pneumonia, such as pneumococcal vaccine and Haemophilus influenza type B (Hib) vaccine, do not provide protection against the new coronavirus.

12/n
column9:
MYTH-10: CAN REGULARLY RINSING YOUR NOSE WITH SALINE HELP PREVENT INFECTION WITH THE NEW CORONAVIRUS?

No. There is no evidence that regularly rinsing the nose with saline has protected people from infection with the new coronavirus. 

13/n
column10:
MYTH-12: DOES THE NEW CORONAVIRUS AFFECT OLDER PEOPLE, OR ARE YOUNGER PEOPLE ALSO SUSCEPTIBLE?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV).

14/n

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.

15/n

column2:
Q. Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?
A. Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.  #coronavirus #coronovirusindia
column3:
Q. What is a CoronaVirus?
A: Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans. In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases. 
#coronavirus #coronavirusindia
column4:
Q. What is COVID-19?
A. COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus. This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.
column5:
Q. What are the symptoms of COVID-19?
A. The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually. #coronavirus
column6:
Q. How fatal is COVID-19?
A. [1/3 ]Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing.
column7: [2/3] Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. About 2% of people with the disease have died. #CoronavirusOutbreak #coronavirusindia
column8:
Q. How does COVID-19 spreads?
A. [1/3] People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales. #CoronaVirusUpdates
column9: [2/3] These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. #CoronaAlert #coronavirus
column10: [3/3] People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick. #coronavirusindia
column11:
Q. Can CoVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?
A. [1/2] The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low. But many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms in the early stages.
column12: [2/2] It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who might be infected but has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill. #Corona #coronavirusindia

column2: What am I trying to say? Everybody has their lane. That a particular trade is booming for someone you know does not mean it will boom for you. You do not know what they know. Forget the glamorous results you see, people's secret efforts settles most of these things outwardly.
column3:
Many times you see many people post their achievements and accolades on social media and you say to yourself 'why not me?' When will it be my own turn? Do they have two heads? etc. 

No! Nothing is wrong with you. Just discover your own lane and press forward. YOU ARE YOU!!!
column4: Most people will not even write about their failures. I AM SUPER PROUD OF MY FAILURES. I failed forward. My failures gave me more lessons and earned me the right and boldness to teach other people about business.
column5: Your failures are a plus. You learn never to do things that same way. Reason I embraced the lean approach. I learnt how to start a business with a very little cost, validate and then grow it. https://t.co/SWKhjcXLsr (@ePoultryNG) is a clear example. I will tell the story some day
column6: By God's Grace (ALL GLORY TO GOD), doing my entrepreneurship career has gotten me recognition home and abroad including from President Obama through his Foundation, the Dutch Government, The Wharton School, Ventures Platform, Embassy of Ireland in Nigeria...
column7: Others are Regional Universities Forum for Capacity Building in Agriculture (RUFORUM) - a network of 121 Vice Chancellors of African Universities, Federal Government of Nigeria, Niger Delta Development Commission (NDDC)...
column8: Small and Medium Enterprises Development Agency of Nigeria (SMEDAN), Embassy of France in Nigeria, Bank of Industry, African Entrepreneurship Awards, Morocco, and several others.
column9: Because of my work as an entrepreneur, I have had FREE, and I mean COMPLETELY FREE trips to some countries in Africa and Europe. It looks like I am bragging but I am actually not.
column10: There were times I applied for these things - put myself forward, pushed and pushed and I always got a NO! For me to share one award, recognition or free travel that came my way, I may have gotten NOs in a multiple of 10, if not 20.
column11: There is a particular annual fellowship I have applied for every year from inception back to back for 6 times in 6 years. I will try again the 7th time this year and look forward to being selected. That is how it is.
column12: You have to develop a thick skin to getting NOs, see them as part of the process and forge ahead. You have to learn from your mistakes and pick up yourself quickly. You have to ultimately look for your own lane and run your race.
column13:
Do not let anyone guilt trip you in believing that this life is a competition. We are not wired to do the same things. 

You also have to stay HUMBLE. Little accolades should not get to your head. If it does, your dreams are so small. Increase the elasticity.
column14:
I moved to another city and drowned myself in Bishop David Oyedepo's book - UNDERSTANDING DIVINE DIRECTION. 

I tried applying for jobs during this period and never did I get one. See, I have a very great CV, good schools, excellent grades and awesome work experience.
column15: As at that time, I had worked for an Impact Accelerator and Consulting firm in Nairobi, did a three year stint in two large commercial banks with several volunteering experiences.
column16: The first test invite I got, I passed and was asked to stay back for an interview same day. I was equally successful and was called to see the CEO which was the last stage of the recruitment process. Maybe my price scared them, I was not called back as promised.
column17:
The second one I ever got much later, I argued with my interviewer who felt he knew everything. LOL. 

I didn't get both jobs. Thank God. I am sure God was looking at me and shaking his head like "see this boy I gave a master-plan trying to run the race of someone else".
column18: Discover your own lane and that is where you will shine effortlessly. This does not in anyway downplay the part of hard work. You will work extra hard and even harder as you go up. Succeeding is easy. Staying successful is not.
column19: That does not mean you will not celebrate your wins. Celebrate them. Enjoy them. But you know what, move on quickly and do the same things you were doing even more.
column20:
I HAVE MY STORY! YOU HAVE YOURS! 

They are never the same even though our results might be similar. It could even bring us plenty money and fame. But it is never the same.
column21:
Finally, success is not even about the money and the fame alone. It is about living your life in a way that you feel happy and fulfilled. Only that, money makes the happiness and fulfillment sweeter. 

Just find your lane, stay there and run your race. 

Dazzol.

Blessed weekend.

Coronavirus disease 2019, or "COVID-19," is an infection caused by specific virus called SARS-CoV-2. The virus first appeared in late 2019 in the city of Wuhan, China. But it has spread quickly through the world

How is COVID-19 spread?
COVID-19 spreads from person to person, similar to the flu. This happens when a sick person coughs or sneezes near other people. Its possible to get sick if you touch a surface that has the virus on it and then touch your mouth, nose, or eyes

column2:
Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?

Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.
column3:
Let¬¥s help fight the spread of the coronavirus. Let¬¥s protect ourselves, our loved ones, colleagues, friends, the community and our country. So here¬¥s a thread of Q&A on coronaviruses (COVID-19) from World Health Organization.
#CovidfreeApril
#CovidfreePhilippines
#CovidfreeWorld
column4:
Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms and don't feel unwell. Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing. 

2/3
column5:
Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. People with fever, cough and difficulty breathing should seek medical attention.

3/3
column6:
How does COVID-19 spread?

People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales. 

1/3
column7:
These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. 

2/3
column8:
People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick.

3/3
column9:
Can CoVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?

The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low. 

1/2
column10:
However, many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms. This is particularly true at the early stages of the disease. It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill.  

2/2

column2:
9. Are antibiotics effective in preventing and treating the new coronavirus?

No, antibiotics do not work against viruses, only bacteria.

The new coronavirus (2019-nCoV) is a virus and, therefore, antibiotics should not be used as a means of prevention or treatment.
column3:
1. Is it safe to receive a letter or a package from China?

Yes, it is safe. People receiving packages from China are not at risk of contracting the new coronavirus. From previous analysis, we know coronaviruses do not survive long on objects, such as letters or packages.
column4:
2. Can spraying alcohol or chlorine all over your body kill the new coronavirus?

No. Spraying alcohol or chlorine on your body will not kill viruses that have already entered your body. Rather, spraying such substances can be harmful to clothes or mucous membranes (eyes, mouth).
column5:
3. How effective are thermal scanners in detecting people infected with the new coronavirus?

Thermal scanners are effective in detecting people who have developed a fever because of infection. However, they cannot detect people who are infected but are not yet sick with fever.
column6:
4. Can an ultraviolet disinfection lamp kill the new coronavirus?

UV lamps should not be used to sterilize hands or other areas of skin as UV radiation can cause skin irritation.
column7:
5. Are hand dryers effective in killing the new coronavirus?

No. Hand dryers are not effective in killing the new coronavirus. To protect yourself against the new coronavirus, you should frequently clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap & water.
column8:
6. Can pets at home spread the new coronavirus (2019-nCoV)?

At present, there is no evidence that companion animals/pets such as dogs or cats can be infected with the new coronavirus. However, it is always a good idea to wash your hands with soap & water after contact with pets.
column9:
7. Do vaccines against pneumonia protect you against the new coronavirus?

No. Vaccines against pneumonia offer no protection against the new coronavirus. The virus is so new and different that it needs its own vaccine. Researchers are trying to develop one & WHO is in support.
column10:
8. Does the new coronavirus affect older people, or are younger people also susceptible?

People of all ages can be infected by the new coronavirus but older people & those with pre-existing medical conditions (such as asthma, diabetes, etc.) appear to be more vulnerable.
column11: WHO advises people of all ages to take steps to protect themselves from the virus, for example by following good hand hygiene and good respiratory hygiene.
column12:
10. Are there any specific medicines to prevent or treat the new coronavirus?

To date, there is no specific medicine recommended to prevent or treat the new coronavirus.

However, those infected with the virus are receiving appropriate care to relieve and treat symptoms.

column2:
What is a coronavirus? 
Coronavirus is a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans.¬†In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from common cold to MERS & SARS.
The most recently discovered coronavirus is COVID-19.
column3:
I've read a lot about Corona virus lately and I think I should share some highlights of the good read.

It's a #Thread, and in form of Q & A.
column4:
What is COVID-19? 

COVID-19 is the INFECTIOUS disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus.

This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.
column5:
The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, & dry cough.

Some patients may have aches & pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea.

These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually. Some people become infected but don‚Äôt develop any symptoms.
column6:
Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. 

People with fever, cough and difficulty breathing should seek medical attention.
column7:
How does COVID-19 spread? 

People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. 

The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales.
column8:
How likely am I to catch COVID-19? 

The risk depends on where you are - and more specifically, whether there is a COVID-19 outbreak unfolding there.
column9:
Should I worry about COVID-19? 

Although illness due to COVID-19 infection is generally mild, especially for children and young adults. 

It is still quite normal for people to worry about how the COVID-19 outbreak will affect them and their loved ones.
column10:
Are antibiotics effective in preventing or treating the COVID-19? 

No. 
Antibiotics do not work against viruses, they only work on bacterial infections. 

COVID-19 is caused by a virus, so antibiotics do not work.
column11:
Is there a vaccine, drug or treatment for COVID-19? 

Not yet. 
To date, there is no vaccine and no specific antiviral medicine to prevent or treat COVID-2019.

However, those affected should receive care to relieve symptoms. 

People with serious illness should be hospitalized.
column12:
Is COVID-19 the same as SARS? 

No. 

The virus that causes COVID-19 and the one that causes Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome (SARS) are related to each other genetically, but they are different. 

SARS is MORE DEADLY but much less infectious than COVID-19.
column13:
Should I wear a mask to protect myself? 

Only wear a mask if you are ill with COVID-19 symptoms (especially coughing) or looking after someone who may have COVID-19.

The mask can only be used once.
If you are not ill/looking after someone who is ill then you are WASTING a mask.
column14:
Can I catch COVID-19 from my pet? 

No. 

There is no evidence that companion animals or pets such as cats and dogs have been infected or could spread the virus that causes COVID-19.
column15:
Is there anything I should not do? 

The following measures ARE NOT effective against COVID-2019 and can be harmful:

1. Smoking

2. Taking traditional herbal remedies 

3. Wearing multiple masks 

4. Taking self-medication such as antibiotics.
column16:
In any case, if you have fever, cough and difficulty breathing seek medical care early to reduce the risk of developing a more severe infection and be sure to share your recent travel history with your health care provider.

#CoronaAlert 
#coronavirus 
#CoronaOutbreak
#Thread

Regularly and thoroughly clean your hands with an alcohol-based hand rub or wash them with soap and water.

column8:

Can COVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?
The main way the disease spreads is through respiratory droplets expelled by someone who is coughing. The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low.

column2:
Q. What is a CoronaVirus?
A: Coronaviruses are a large family of viruses which may cause illness in animals or humans. In humans, several coronaviruses are known to cause respiratory infections ranging from the common cold to more severe diseases. 
#coronavirus #coronavirusindia
column3:
Q. What is COVID-19?
A. COVID-19 is the infectious disease caused by the most recently discovered coronavirus. This new virus and disease were unknown before the outbreak began in Wuhan, China, in December 2019.
column4:
Q. What are the symptoms of COVID-19?
A. The most common symptoms of COVID-19 are fever, tiredness, and dry cough. Some patients may have aches and pains, nasal congestion, runny nose, sore throat or diarrhea. These symptoms are usually mild and begin gradually. #coronavirus
column5:
Q. How fatal is COVID-19?
A. [1/3 ]Most people (about 80%) recover from the disease without needing special treatment. Around 1 out of every 6 people who gets COVID-19 becomes seriously ill and develops difficulty breathing.
column6: [2/3] Older people, and those with underlying medical problems like high blood pressure, heart problems or diabetes, are more likely to develop serious illness. About 2% of people with the disease have died. #CoronavirusOutbreak #coronavirusindia
column7:
Q. How does COVID-19 spreads?
A. [1/3] People can catch COVID-19 from others who have the virus. The disease can spread from person to person through small droplets from the nose or mouth which are spread when a person with COVID-19 coughs or exhales. #CoronaVirusUpdates
column8: [2/3] These droplets land on objects and surfaces around the person. Other people then catch COVID-19 by touching these objects or surfaces, then touching their eyes, nose or mouth. #CoronaAlert #coronavirus
column9: [3/3] People can also catch COVID-19 if they breathe in droplets from a person with COVID-19 who coughs out or exhales droplets. This is why it is important to stay more than 1 meter (3 feet) away from a person who is sick. #coronavirusindia
column10:
Q. Can the virus that causes COVID-19 be transmitted through the air?
A. Studies to date suggest that the virus that causes COVID-19 is mainly transmitted through contact with respiratory droplets rather than through the air.  #coronavirus #coronovirusindia
column11:
Q. Can CoVID-19 be caught from a person who has no symptoms?
A. [1/2] The risk of catching COVID-19 from someone with no symptoms at all is very low. But many people with COVID-19 experience only mild symptoms in the early stages.
column12: [2/2] It is therefore possible to catch COVID-19 from someone who might be infected but has, for example, just a mild cough and does not feel ill. #Corona #coronavirusindia
